{"title_page": "Kangaroo Point, Queensland", "text_new": "{{For|other places named Kangaroo Point|Kangaroo Point (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{GeoGroup}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type     = suburb\n| name     = Kangaroo Point\n| city     = Brisbane\n| state    = qld\n| image    = Story Bridge Side.jpg      \n| caption  = Kangaroo Point, underneath the [[Story Bridge]]\n| coordinates         = {{coord|-27.4747|153.0386|type:city_region:AU-QLD|display=inline,title}}\n| pop                 = 8063\n| pop_year            = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n| pop_footnotes       = <ref name=Census2016/>\n| established         = \n| postcode            = 4169\n| area                = 1.8\n| timezone            = [[AEST]]\n| utc                 = +10:00\n| lga      = [[City of Brisbane]] ([[The Gabba Ward]])<ref name=\"TheGabbaWard\">{{cite web|title=The Gabba Ward|url=https://www.brisbane.qld.gov.au/about-council/governance-strategy/councillors-wards/the-gabba-ward|website=Brisbane City Council|publisher=Brisbane City Council|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n| stategov = [[Electoral district of South Brisbane|South Brisbane]]\n| fedgov   = [[Division of Griffith|Griffith]]\n| dist1               = \n| dir1                = \n| location1           = \n| dist2               = \n| dir2                = \n| location2           = \n| dist3               = \n| dir3                = \n| location3           = \n| dist4               = \n| dir4                = \n| location4           =\n| near-n   = [[Fortitude Valley]]\n| near-ne  = [[New Farm, Queensland|New Farm]]\n| near-e   = [[New Farm, Queensland|New Farm]]\n| near-se  = [[East Brisbane]]\n| near-s   = [[Woolloongabba]]\n| near-sw  = [[South Brisbane]]\n| near-w   = [[Brisbane central business district|Brisbane City]]\n| near-nw  = [[Brisbane central business district|Brisbane City]]\n}}\n\n'''Kangaroo Point''' is an inner southern [[Suburbs and localities (Australia)|suburb]] in the [[City of Brisbane]], [[Queensland]], Australia.<ref name=qpnl>{{cite QPN|44658|Kangaroo Point|suburb in City of Brisbane|accessdate=25 January 2020}}</ref> In the {{CensusAU|2016}}, Kangaroo Point had a population of 8,063 people.<ref name=Census2016/>\n\nThe suburb features two prominent attractions, the [[Story Bridge]] and [[Kangaroo Point Cliffs]].\n\n== Geography ==\nKangaroo Point is located directly east across the [[Brisbane River]] from the [[Brisbane central business district]], but being on the south side of the river is normally regarded as a southern suburb.\n\nKangaroo Point is located on a [[peninsula]] formed of harder [[rhyolite]] rock which the [[Brisbane River]] flows around. On the northern tip of the peninsula the [[Story Bridge]] connects it to the [[Brisbane central business district|central business district]] and the suburb of [[Fortitude Valley]]. The suburb of [[Woolloongabba]] is located to the south. The six-lane Main Street runs from Story Bridge to Woolloongabba. The landscape of Kangaroo Point is predominantly high rise apartments towards the tip of the peninsula while the southern end is predominantly low-medium density apartments and [[Queenslander (architecture)|Queenslander]] type houses.\n\nAt the northern tip of the peninsula is Captain Burke Park ({{Coord|-27.4653|153.0350|type:landmark_region:AU-QLD|display=|name=Captain Burke Park}}) with the [[Holman Street ferry wharf]], barbeques, picnic facilities, playground, and outdoor fitness facilities.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbane.qld.gov.au/things-to-see-and-do/council-venues-and-precincts/parks/parks-by-suburb/kangaroo-point-parks|title=Kangaroo Point parks|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Brisbane City Council]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:StateLibQld 1 126315 Naval Stores at Kangaroo Point, seen from across the Brisbane River.jpg|thumb|right|The Queensland [[Naval Stores, Kangaroo Point|Navy's main stores]] below the Kangaroo Point cliffs, with the gunship ''Paluma'' moored in the Brisbane River in the 1890s.]]\n[[File:StateLibQld 1 101720.jpg|thumb|Kangaroo Point Ferry Terminal ca. 1928]]\nBefore British [[colonization|settlement]], Kangaroo Point was settled by the [[Turrbal]] people.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dakibudtcha.com.au/turrbal_history.htm |title=Turrbal History |access-date=11 February 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091026221727/http://www.dakibudtcha.com.au/turrbal_history.htm |archive-date=26 October 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It is one of the earliest suburbs settled in Brisbane and subsequently, is one of Brisbane's oldest suburbs, rich in history and character. It had a reputation for violent and rowdy street gangs around the 1900s, with a number of street riots.<ref name=\"sohf\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,26565140-5008700,00.html|title=School of hard knocks on cliffs|date=10 January 2010|newspaper=The Sunday Mail|accessdate=21 February 2011|publisher=Queensland Newspapers|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100131070155/http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,26565140-5008700,00.html|archive-date=31 January 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1823, explorer [[John Oxley]] described Kangaroo Point as a \"jungle, fringed with mangroves with the higher land open forest, covered with grass\". During the time of the subsequent [[Moreton Bay penal colony|convict settlement]] (1825\u20131841), Kangaroo Point was cleared and used for cultivation of crops. Subsequently, the area was opened up for free settlement, the first land sales taking place on 13 December 1843. Among the early purchasers was Captain [[John Clements Wickham]], the Police Magistrate and later [[Resident (title)|Government Resident]]. Surveyor [[James Warner (surveyor)|James Warner]] built the first house at Kangaroo Point in 1844.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.saintmarys.org.au/history.htm |title=Saint Mary's: Our Rich History |access-date=11 February 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100503111313/http://www.saintmarys.org.au/history.htm |archive-date=3 May 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nKangaroo Point's first school was opened in 1861 by the Church of England. It came under the control of the Board of Education in 1867 and consisted of a boys department and a girls department. A separate Girls and Infants school opened on 2 March 1874. This was replaced by the Kangaroo Point Girls School and the Kangaroo Point Infants School which both opened on 20 January 1890. The Kangaroo Point Boys School, Girls School and Infants School closed on 28 April 1950 and amalgamated to become the Kangaroo Point State School.<ref>[http://www.newsphotos.com.au/ImageDetail.asp?RefNum=87105499 BCM 1960 : Kangaroo Point State School in Main St]</ref> The Kangaroo Point State School closed on 30 June 1965.<ref>{{Cite QSA Agency|3303|Kangaroo Point State School|31 March 2020}}</ref> The site was subsequently redeveloped as a [[Technical and further education|TAFE]] college, on the corner of River Terrace and Main Street. In January 2010 this site was redeveloped into parkland extending the Kangaroo Point Cliffs Park ({{Coord|-27.4753|153.0352|type:landmark_region:AU-QLD|display=|name=Kangaroo Point Cliffs Park}}).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/wrecking-ball-falls-on-south-bank-tafe-20090422-af12.html|title=Wrecking ball falls on South Bank TAFE|last=Hurst|first=Daniel|date=2009-04-22|website=Brisbane Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn September 1865, 42 allotments of portion 35 of Kangaroo Point were advertised to be auctioned for sale by Arthur Martin & Co.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article1278397|title=Classified Advertising|date=12 September 1865|newspaper=[[The Brisbane Courier]]|accessdate=24 September 2019|issue=2,378|location=Queensland, Australia|volume=XX|page=6|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> A map advertising the auction contained a diagram of subdivisions 1 to 31 situated between Ipswich Road and the Brisbane River.<ref>{{Cite document|title=City property plan of subdivision of portion no. 35, Kangaroo Point|last=|first=|date=18 September 1865|hdl = 10462/deriv/18688}}</ref>\n\nSt Joseph's Catholic Primary School was founded by [[Mary MacKillop]] and opened on 19 March 1870 in Hubert Street in One Mile Swamp (now [[Woolloongabba]]) with 70 students. In January 1871, the school relocated to Leopold Street (not Leopard Street) at Kangaroo Point into an unlined timber building with a shingle roof on land provided by James Toohey. In 1879 the [[Sisters of Mercy]] took over the operation of the school, following a dispute between MacKillop and the [[Roman Catholic Bishop of Brisbane|Catholic Bishop of Brisbane]].<ref name=\"qfhs\">{{Citation|author1=Queensland Family History Society|title=Queensland schools past and present|date=2010|edition=Version 1.01|publisher=[[Queensland Family History Society]]|isbn=978-1-921171-26-0}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stjosephskpt.qld.edu.au/About%20Us/Pages/St-Joseph%27s-History.aspx|title=St Joseph's History|last=|first=|date=|website=St Joseph's Primary School|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109100645/http://www.stjosephskpt.qld.edu.au/About%20Us/Pages/St-Joseph's-History.aspx|archive-date=2019-11-09|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 1887, the [[Yungaba Immigration Centre]] was built on Main Street at Kangaroo Point to replace the poor facilities at the existing centre in [[William Street, Brisbane|William Street]].<ref name=\"yungaba\" />\n\nIn June 1888, six allotments, being subdivisions 1 to 6 of subdivisions 7 to 11 of portions 68 in the Parish of Kangaroo Point, on Walmsley Street between the Garden Point Ferry and Main Street were advertised to be auctioned for sale by Simon Fraser & Son.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article177865101|title=Advertising|date=19 June 1888|newspaper=[[Telegraph (Brisbane)|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=24 September 2019|issue=4,895|location=Queensland, Australia|page=8|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> A map advertising the auction contained a local sketch by the surveyors, Hamilton & Raff.<ref>{{Cite document|title=Choice allotments Walmsley Street, Kangaroo Point|last=|first=|date=23 June 1888|hdl = 10462/deriv/398712}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1928, 19 subdivisions adjacent to the Brisbane River and titled \"Town Reach River Sites\" were advertised to be auctioned for sale by Isles, Love & Co Limited. A map advertising the auction includes an aerial photograph and a panoramic photograph of the area.<ref>{{Cite document|title=Town Reach River sites|last=|first=|date=22 September 1928|hdl = 10462/deriv/258186}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article21350173|title=Advertising|date=1 September 1928|newspaper=[[The Brisbane Courier]]|accessdate=24 September 2019|issue=22,028|location=Queensland, Australia|page=28|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nFor many years the suburb was dominated by the factories of heavy engineering businesses, particularly those involved in the maritime industry, such as [[Evans Deakin and Company|Evans Deakin]], Buzzacott & Co and [[Evans, Anderson, Phelan & Co]]. Evans Deakin built the largest ship ever constructed on the Brisbane River, the 66,000 tonne oil tanker ''Robert Miller'', which became adrift in the river during the [[1974 Brisbane flood]].<ref name=\"b150s\">{{cite book|title=Brisbane 150 Stories|author=McBride, Frank|publisher=Brisbane City Council Publication|year=2009|isbn=978-1-876091-60-6|pages=250\u2013251|display-authors=etal}}</ref> The last vessel to be built by Evans Deakin was an oil rig called ''Southern Cross''. The company vacated the site in 1976,<ref name=\"b150s\" /> with it later being redeveloped for high-rise accommodation.\n\nStone was quarried from the cliffs and used as building material. Until the 1930s, Evans Anderson & Phelan built steam locomotives at their Kangaroo Point works for [[Queensland Rail]]ways, however their works were not located near a railway, so the completed locomotives were delivered along Main Street on temporary track.\n\nUntil the federation of the Australian colonies in 1901, the Queensland Navy's main storage facility was located in the suburb. The first ship-based radio transmission in Australia was made between [[HMQS Gayundah|HMAS ''Gayundah'']] and the buildings in 1903. The naval stores buildings were occupied by the [[Royal Australian Navy]] until 1959, and then by the [[Australian Army]] until 1984. The heritage-listed buildings are now used by an adventure company focussing on river activities and rock climbing.\n\nThe opening of the Story Bridge ({{Coord|-27.4693|153.0359|type:landmark_region:AU-QLD|display=|name=Story Bridge (Kangaroo Point end)}}) in July 1940 was the most significant development of the suburb. [[Trolleybuses in Brisbane|Trolleybuses]] operated by the [[Brisbane City Council]] linked the suburb with Fortitude Valley via the Story Bridge from 1953 to 1969, running along Main Street from Woolloongabba and other eastern suburbs.<ref>{{cite book|title=Brisbane's tramways: The last decade|author1=Clark, H.R.|author2=Keenan, D.R.|publisher=Transit Press|year=1977|isbn=978-0-909338-01-5}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 2% of sex workers in Queensland were street prostitutes operating in inner Brisbane suburbs such as Kangaroo Point.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pla.qld.gov.au/Resources/PLA/reportsPublications/documents/Select%20Sex%20Industry%20Statistics.pdf|title=Select Sex Industry Statistics|date=December 2011|website=www.pla.qld.gov.au/|publisher=Prostitution Licensing Authority|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190314172936/http://www.pla.qld.gov.au/Resources/PLA/reportsPublications/documents/Select%20Sex%20Industry%20Statistics.pdf|archive-date=14 March 2019|accessdate=30 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/questnews/southeast/calls-for-police-crackdown-on-prostitution-in-inner-brisbane-suburb/news-story/4c78d88535b8ec6f4ccac03d957c0acd|title=Prostitution crackdown: Calls for police to crackdown at inner Brisbane Suburb|date=3 May 2017|website=news.com.au|publisher=The Courier Mail|accessdate=30 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the {{CensusAU|2016}}, Kangaroo Point had a population of 8,063 people.<ref name=Census2016>{{Census 2016 AUS|id=SSC31496|name=Kangaroo Point (SSC)|accessdate=20 October 2018|quick=on}}</ref>\n\n==Attractions==\nKangaroo Point is a popular recreation spot, conveniently close to the city and the [[South Bank Parklands, Brisbane|South Bank Parklands]]. The [[Kangaroo Point Cliffs]], situated on the east bank of the city bend of the Brisbane River north of the Maritime Museum, opposite [[Riverstage]] and the [[Queensland University of Technology]] at [[Gardens Point, Brisbane|Gardens Point]]. The Look-out at Kangaroo Point is also included as one of the stops of [[Brisbane Transport]]'s City Sights bus service. Kangaroo Point is also home to one of less than 200 Mormon temples in the world {as of August 2015}. Kangaroo Point is also home to Ellis Street, one of the 20 steepest hills in Brisbane according to Brisbane City Council. Kangaroo Point is also home to the more-than-160-year-old St Mary's Anglican Church.\n\n[[File:Brisbane During Twilight.jpg|thumb|right|Brisbane's [[Brisbane central business district|CBD]] from Kangaroo Point cliffs]]\nThe cliffs are a popular picnic, [[rock climbing]] and [[abseiling]] site. The steepness of the cliffs was increased by quarrying operations which mined the [[volcanic rock]] or [[rhyolite]] [[lava]] flows which form the cliffs. The lava was deposited in the [[Triassic]] Period about 230 million years ago and filled up an ancient river valley. They currently form the banks of the Brisbane River.\n\nThe [[Story Bridge]] is a prominent landmark. It is able to be climbed with authorised tourist groups and provides the main means of access to the north of Brisbane. Directly under the bridge is the Story Bridge Hotel, and [[Yungaba Immigration Centre|Yungaba]], one of Brisbane's most unusual and iconic landmarks.<ref>[http://www.brisbane-australia.com/kangaroo-point.html Kangaroo Point] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022154508/http://www.brisbane-australia.com/kangaroo-point.html |date=22 October 2013 }} Brisbane Tourism Guide. Retrieved on 2013-11-07.</ref>\n\nThe ''Kangaroo Point Natural History Project'' was implemented by the council in 2013 to recognise the contribution by some of Queensland's pioneering scientists and researchers from the area. Along a heritage trail through the CT White and James Warner parks are a series of signs and sculptures to commemorate their lives and work: [[Cyril Tenison White]] (government botanist), [[Frederick Manson Bailey]] (colonial botanist), [[Silvester Diggles]] (naturalist), [[Oscar Werner Tiegs]] (entomologist and zoologist), [[James Warner (surveyor)|James Warner]] (surveyor), and [[Harry Oakman]] (landscape artist).<ref>{{cite web|title=Kangaroo Point Natural History Project|url=http://www.brisbane.qld.gov.au/facilities-recreation/sports-and-leisure/walking/walking-trails/heritage-trails/kangaroo-point-natural-history-project/index.htm|publisher=Brisbane City Council|accessdate=18 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219020826/http://www.brisbane.qld.gov.au/facilities-recreation/sports-and-leisure/walking/walking-trails/heritage-trails/kangaroo-point-natural-history-project/index.htm|archive-date=19 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Transport==\n[[Image:Kangaroo Point Cliffs.jpg|thumb|right|[[Kangaroo Point Cliffs]] after sunset]]\n[[File:Brisbane Lights at Night from Kangaroo Point.jpg|thumb|right|Walkway along the cliffs]]\nBy bus the suburb is serviced by the [[South East Busway]] transit line and buses along Main Street and Shafstons Avenue. By road Kangaroo Point residents rely on the [[Story Bridge]] and [[Captain Cook Bridge, Brisbane|Captain Cook Bridge]] for access to the north, and the [[Pacific Motorway (Brisbane-Ballina)|Southeast Freeway]] for access to the south. Main Street connects the Story Bridge through the suburb to the South East Freeway. Bicycle paths run along the [[Brisbane River]] from South Bank to and over the Story Bridge. The bicycle paths are heavily used by cyclists, roller skaters and pedestrians.\n\n[[Transdev Brisbane Ferries|CityFerry]] service from the [[Eagle Street Pier ferry wharf|Eagle Street Pier]] in the CBD and the [[Sydney Street ferry wharf|Sydney Street Pier]] in New Farm to [[Holman Street ferry wharf]] near the peak of Kangaroo Point, [[Thornton Street ferry wharf]] on the west side of the point, or [[Dockside ferry wharf]] on the east side. CityCat services do not directly service Kangaroo Point.<ref>[http://www.translink.com.au/qt/translin.nsf/ReferenceLookup/080804_map_network_ferry.pdf/$file/080804_map_network_ferry.pdf Translink Ferry Map] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720195740/http://www.translink.com.au/qt/translin.nsf/ReferenceLookup/080804_map_network_ferry.pdf/$file/080804_map_network_ferry.pdf |date=20 July 2008 }}.</ref>\n\nThe [[North South Bypass Tunnel|M7 Clem Jones Tunnel]], a toll tunnel, which opened in March 2010, has a connection on Shafston Avenue. It diverts some traffic travelling through the suburb while providing an additional transport route for residents.\n\nA green bridge was proposed in 2010 to the west to connect Kangaroo Point to Brisibane City and to the east to connect Kangaroo Point to Merthyr Road [[New Farm, Queensland|New Farm]], but at March 2020  these projects have not been progressed.<ref name=\"bcob\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/queensland/brisbane-city-of-bridges-20100322-qr4y.html |title=Brisbane, city of bridges? |accessdate=14 March 2013 |date=23 March 2010 |work=Brisbane Times |publisher=Fairfax Media |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110204103451/http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/queensland/brisbane-city-of-bridges-20100322-qr4y.html |archive-date=4 February 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Cross River Rail]] tunnel is planned to connect under Kangaroo Point Cliffs from Woolloongabba to an [[Albert Street, Brisbane|Albert Street]] railway station.\n\n==Demographics==\nIn the {{CensusAU|2011}} of Population and Housing, the population of Kangaroo Point postcode area was 7,000 people, in an area of 1.3 square kilometres.<ref name=\"census11\">{{Census 2011 AUS|id=SSC30845 |name=Kangaroo Point (State Suburb)|accessdate=14 March 2013 |quick=on}}</ref> The population was 48.3% females and 51.7% males. The median age of the Kangaroo Point population was 35 years of age, 2 years below the Australian median.  53.1% of people living in Kangaroo Point were born in Australia, compared to the national average of 69.8%; the next most common countries of birth were New Zealand 5.2%, England 4.4%, India 1.6%, Ireland 1.6%, Taiwan 1.2%.  69.6% of people spoke only English at home; the next most popular languages were 1.9% Mandarin, 1.8% Spanish, 0.9% Cantonese, 0.9% Nepali, 0.9% Italian. It has one of the city's highest proportion of residents living in flats, units or apartments (78.8%). Residents in stand alone houses make up only 16.6% of the population. 59.9% of residents are renters while only 18.7% fully own their dwelling. According to REIQ, the median house price in Kangaroo Point for the calendar year 2010 was $658,500.<ref>[http://reiq.com/Suburbs.aspx?su=Kangaroo%20Point&postcode=4169&type=1 Kangaroo Point]. REIQ Suburb profile. Retrieved 14 March 2013.</ref>\n\n==Education==\nSt Joseph's Primary School is a Catholic primary (Prep-6) school for boys and girls at 26-36 Leopard Street ({{coord|-27.4829|153.0329|type:edu_region:AU-QLD|name=St Joseph's Primary School}}).<ref name=\"SchoolList2018\">{{cite web|url=https://data.qld.gov.au/dataset/state-and-non-state-school-details/resource/5b39065c-df32-415c-994c-5ff12f8de997|title=State and non-state school details|date=9 July 2018|publisher=[[Queensland Government]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121065959/https://data.qld.gov.au/dataset/state-and-non-state-school-details/resource/5b39065c-df32-415c-994c-5ff12f8de997|archivedate=21 November 2018|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stjosephskpt.qld.edu.au|title=St Joseph's Primary School|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref> In 2017, the school had an enrolment of 318 students with 24 teachers (18 full-time equivalent) and 16 non-teaching staff (9 full-time equivalent).<ref name=\"ACARA2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acara.edu.au/docs/default-source/default-document-library/school-profile-20172c7b12404c94637ead88ff00003e0139.xlsx?sfvrsn=0|title=ACARA School Profile 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181122010027/http://www.acara.edu.au/docs/default-source/default-document-library/school-profile-20172c7b12404c94637ead88ff00003e0139.xlsx?sfvrsn=0|archivedate=22 November 2018|accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThere are no government schools in Kangaroo Point. The nearest government primary school is [[East Brisbane State School]] in [[East Brisbane, Queensland|East Brisbane]]. The nearest government secondary school is Coorparoo Secondary College in [[Coorparoo, Queensland|Coorparoo]].<ref name=\"globe\">{{Queensland Globe|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFor tertiary studies, Kangaroo Point is host to Shafston International College and the [[Aboriginal Centre for the Performing Arts (ACPA)]] (which has now moved to the Judith Wright Centre in Fortitude Valley) and was host to a Southbank Institute of TAFE campus until its demolition in 2009. Directly across the river from the cliffs is the [[Queensland University of Technology]] (Gardens Point campus) and in an adjacent suburb, the main campus for TAFE Queensland Brisbane (South Bank).\n\n==Heritage listings==\n[[File:Yungaba Immigration Centre riverside lawn.jpg|thumb|[[Yungaba Immigration Centre]] and riverside lawn, 2015]]\n[[File:St Nicholas Russian Orthodox Cathedral.jpg|thumb|[[St Nicholas Russian Orthodox Cathedral]], 2015]]\nKangaroo Point has a number of [[heritage-listed]] sites, including:\n* 34 Amesbury Street: former [[Naval Stores, Kangaroo Point|Naval Stores]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15014|Naval Stores (former)|600239|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 94 Baines Street: [[Raymond Park (West) Air Raid Shelter]]<ref>{{cite QHR|19599|Raymond Park (West) Air Raid Shelter|602478|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 23 Castlebar Street: [[Shafston House]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15016|Shafston House|600241|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 116 Holman Street: [[Holman Street ferry wharf|Holman Street Ferry Terminal]]<ref>{{cite QHR|19566|Holman Street Ferry Terminal|602445|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 9 Leopard Street: [[Lamb House, Kangaroo Point|Lamb House]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15017|Home|600242|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* Lower River Terrace: [[Kangaroo Point Cliffs]]<ref>{{cite QHR|19520|Kangaroo Point Cliffs|602400|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 76 Lower River Terrace: [[Cliffside Apartments]]<ref>{{cite QHR|16411|Cliffside Apartments|601650|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 102 Main Street: [[Yungaba Immigration Centre]]<ref name=yungaba>{{cite QHR|15020|Yungaba Immigration Depot|600245|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 255 Main Street: [[Sunnyside, Kangaroo Point|Sunnyside]]<ref>{{cite QHR|16547|Sunnyside|601810|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 261 - 267 Main Street: [[Silverwells]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15018|Silverwells|600243|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 433, 447 & 449 Main Street: [[St Mary's Anglican Church, Kangaroo Point|St Mary's Anglican Church]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15019|St Mary's Anglican Church|600244|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 2 Scott Street: [[Scott Street Flats]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15936|Scott Street Flats|601171|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 69 Shafston Avenue: [[Leckhampton, Kangaroo Point|Leckhampton]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15021|Leckhampton|600246|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 330-334B Vulture Street: [[St Nicholas Russian Orthodox Cathedral]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15133|St Nicholas Russian Orthodox Cathedral|600358|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 184 Wellington Road: [[Raymond Park (East) Air Raid Shelter]]<ref>{{cite QHR|19600|Raymond Park (East) Air Raid Shelter|602479|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==<!-- Please respect alphabetical order, only notable people (with an article or citations that demonstrate notability) -->\n* [[Frederick Manson Bailey]], Australian botanist\n* [[Peter Burge (cricketer)|Peter Burge]], Australian cricketer\n* [[James Davis (escaped convict)|James Davis]], convict and pioneer\n* [[Silvester Diggles]], Australian musician and ornithologist\n* [[Alec Hurwood]], Australian cricketer\n* [[John Lavarack]], A Former [[Governor of Queensland]]\n* [[Frank Payne (artist)|Frances Mallalieu Payne]] (1885-1976) artist and illustrator<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/payne-frances-mallalieu-frank-11354|title = Payne, Frances Mallalieu (Frank) (1885\u20131976)|date = 2000|accessdate = 30 March 2015|website = Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher = |last = Philp|first = Angela|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150403003634/http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/payne-frances-mallalieu-frank-11354|archive-date = 3 April 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n* [[Alfred John Raymond]], alderman for Kangaroo Point and mayor of Brisbane in 1912\n* [[Charles Jackson Stewart]], (1876-1954) hotel keeper at the Criterion Hotel, George Street<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/stewart-charles-jackson-11766|title=Stewart, Charles Jackson (1876\u20131954)|last=Cook|first=Margaret|date=2002|website=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=|accessdate=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402211049/http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/stewart-charles-jackson-11766|archive-date=2 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Oscar Werner Tiegs]], Australian zoologist\n* [[Cyril Tenison White]], Australian botanist\n* [[Christopher Wrench]], organist\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Kangaroo Point, Queensland}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://queenslandplaces.com.au/kangaroo-point|title=Kangaroo Point|publisher=Centre for the Government of Queensland, University of Queensland|website=Queensland Places}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191806/http://www.epa.qld.gov.au/projects/heritage/index.cgi?place=600239&back=1|title= Information on the naval stores from the Queensland Heritage Register}}\n*[https://www.escapestock.com/kangaroo-point/ Exploring Kangaroo Point]\n\n{{Suburbs of Brisbane City Council}}\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Brisbane]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1843]]\n[[Category:Kangaroo Point, Queensland]]\n[[Category:1843 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Pre-Separation Queensland]]\n[[Category:Red-light districts in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other places named Kangaroo Point|Kangaroo Point (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{GeoGroup}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type     = suburb\n| name     = Kangaroo Point\n| city     = Brisbane\n| state    = qld\n| image    = Story Bridge Side.jpg      \n| caption  = Kangaroo Point, underneath the [[Story Bridge]]\n| coordinates         = {{coord|-27.4747|153.0386|type:city_region:AU-QLD|display=inline,title}}\n| pop                 = 8063\n| pop_year            = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n| pop_footnotes       = <ref name=Census2016/>\n| established         = \n| postcode            = 4169\n| area                = 1.8\n| timezone            = [[AEST]]\n| utc                 = +10:00\n| lga      = [[City of Brisbane]] ([[The Gabba Ward]])<ref name=\"TheGabbaWard\">{{cite web|title=The Gabba Ward|url=https://www.brisbane.qld.gov.au/about-council/governance-strategy/councillors-wards/the-gabba-ward|website=Brisbane City Council|publisher=Brisbane City Council|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n| stategov = [[Electoral district of South Brisbane|South Brisbane]]\n| fedgov   = [[Division of Griffith|Griffith]]\n| dist1               = \n| dir1                = \n| location1           = \n| dist2               = \n| dir2                = \n| location2           = \n| dist3               = \n| dir3                = \n| location3           = \n| dist4               = \n| dir4                = \n| location4           =\n| near-n   = [[Fortitude Valley]]\n| near-ne  = [[New Farm, Queensland|New Farm]]\n| near-e   = [[New Farm, Queensland|New Farm]]\n| near-se  = [[East Brisbane]]\n| near-s   = [[Woolloongabba]]\n| near-sw  = [[South Brisbane]]\n| near-w   = [[Brisbane central business district|Brisbane City]]\n| near-nw  = [[Brisbane central business district|Brisbane City]]\n}}\n\n'''Kangaroo Point''' is an inner southern [[Suburbs and localities (Australia)|suburb]] in the [[City of Brisbane]], [[Queensland]], Australia.<ref name=qpnl>{{cite QPN|44658|Kangaroo Point|suburb in City of Brisbane|accessdate=25 January 2020}}</ref> In the {{CensusAU|2016}}, Kangaroo Point had a population of 8,063 people.<ref name=Census2016/>\n\nThe suburb features two prominent attractions, the [[Story Bridge]] and [[Kangaroo Point Cliffs]].\n\n== Geography ==\nKangaroo Point is located directly east across the [[Brisbane River]] from the [[Brisbane central business district]], but being on the south side of the river is normally regarded as a southern suburb.\n\nKangaroo Point is located on a [[peninsula]] formed of harder [[rhyolite]] rock which the [[Brisbane River]] flows around. On the northern tip of the peninsula the [[Story Bridge]] connects it to the [[Brisbane central business district|central business district]] and the suburb of [[Fortitude Valley]]. The suburb of [[Woolloongabba]] is located to the south. The six-lane Main Street runs from Story Bridge to Woolloongabba. The landscape of Kangaroo Point is predominantly high rise apartments towards the tip of the peninsula while the southern end is predominantly low-medium density apartments and [[Queenslander (architecture)|Queenslander]] type houses.\n\nAt the northern tip of the peninsula is Captain Burke Park ({{Coord|-27.4653|153.0350|type:landmark_region:AU-QLD|display=|name=Captain Burke Park}}) with the [[Holman Street ferry wharf]], barbeques, picnic facilities, playgound, and outdoor fitness facilities.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbane.qld.gov.au/things-to-see-and-do/council-venues-and-precincts/parks/parks-by-suburb/kangaroo-point-parks|title=Kangaroo Point parks|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Brisbane City Council]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:StateLibQld 1 126315 Naval Stores at Kangaroo Point, seen from across the Brisbane River.jpg|thumb|right|The Queensland [[Naval Stores, Kangaroo Point|Navy's main stores]] below the Kangaroo Point cliffs, with the gunship ''Paluma'' moored in the Brisbane River in the 1890s.]]\n[[File:StateLibQld 1 101720.jpg|thumb|Kangaroo Point Ferry Terminal ca. 1928]]\nBefore British [[colonization|settlement]], Kangaroo Point was settled by the [[Turrbal]] people.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dakibudtcha.com.au/turrbal_history.htm |title=Turrbal History |access-date=11 February 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091026221727/http://www.dakibudtcha.com.au/turrbal_history.htm |archive-date=26 October 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It is one of the earliest suburbs settled in Brisbane and subsequently, is one of Brisbane's oldest suburbs, rich in history and character. It had a reputation for violent and rowdy street gangs around the 1900s, with a number of street riots.<ref name=\"sohf\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,26565140-5008700,00.html|title=School of hard knocks on cliffs|date=10 January 2010|newspaper=The Sunday Mail|accessdate=21 February 2011|publisher=Queensland Newspapers|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100131070155/http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,26565140-5008700,00.html|archive-date=31 January 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1823, explorer [[John Oxley]] described Kangaroo Point as a \"jungle, fringed with mangroves with the higher land open forest, covered with grass\". During the time of the subsequent [[Moreton Bay penal colony|convict settlement]] (1825\u20131841), Kangaroo Point was cleared and used for cultivation of crops. Subsequently, the area was opened up for free settlement, the first land sales taking place on 13 December 1843. Among the early purchasers was Captain [[John Clements Wickham]], the Police Magistrate and later [[Resident (title)|Government Resident]]. Surveyor [[James Warner (surveyor)|James Warner]] built the first house at Kangaroo Point in 1844.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.saintmarys.org.au/history.htm |title=Saint Mary's: Our Rich History |access-date=11 February 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100503111313/http://www.saintmarys.org.au/history.htm |archive-date=3 May 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nKangaroo Point's first school was opened in 1861 by the Church of England. It came under the control of the Board of Education in 1867 and consisted of a boys department and a girls department. A separate Girls and Infants school opened on 2 March 1874. This was replaced by the Kangaroo Point Girls School and the Kangaroo Point Infants School which both opened on 20 January 1890. The Kangaroo Point Boys School, Girls School and Infants School closed on 28 April 1950 and amalgamated to become the Kangaroo Point State School.<ref>[http://www.newsphotos.com.au/ImageDetail.asp?RefNum=87105499 BCM 1960 : Kangaroo Point State School in Main St]</ref> The Kangaroo Point State School closed on 30 June 1965.<ref>{{Cite QSA Agency|3303|Kangaroo Point State School|31 March 2020}}</ref> The site was subsequently redeveloped as a [[Technical and further education|TAFE]] college, on the corner of River Terrace and Main Street. In January 2010 this site was redeveloped into parkland extending the Kangaroo Point Cliffs Park ({{Coord|-27.4753|153.0352|type:landmark_region:AU-QLD|display=|name=Kangaroo Point Cliffs Park}}).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/wrecking-ball-falls-on-south-bank-tafe-20090422-af12.html|title=Wrecking ball falls on South Bank TAFE|last=Hurst|first=Daniel|date=2009-04-22|website=Brisbane Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn September 1865, 42 allotments of portion 35 of Kangaroo Point were advertised to be auctioned for sale by Arthur Martin & Co.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article1278397|title=Classified Advertising|date=12 September 1865|newspaper=[[The Brisbane Courier]]|accessdate=24 September 2019|issue=2,378|location=Queensland, Australia|volume=XX|page=6|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> A map advertising the auction contained a diagram of subdivisions 1 to 31 situated between Ipswich Road and the Brisbane River.<ref>{{Cite document|title=City property plan of subdivision of portion no. 35, Kangaroo Point|last=|first=|date=18 September 1865|hdl = 10462/deriv/18688}}</ref>\n\nSt Joseph's Catholic Primary School was founded by [[Mary MacKillop]] and opened on 19 March 1870 in Hubert Street in One Mile Swamp (now [[Woolloongabba]]) with 70 students. In January 1871, the school relocated to Leopold Street (not Leopard Street) at Kangaroo Point into an unlined timber building with a shingle roof on land provided by James Toohey. In 1879 the [[Sisters of Mercy]] took over the operation of the school, following a dispute between MacKillop and the [[Roman Catholic Bishop of Brisbane|Catholic Bishop of Brisbane]].<ref name=\"qfhs\">{{Citation|author1=Queensland Family History Society|title=Queensland schools past and present|date=2010|edition=Version 1.01|publisher=[[Queensland Family History Society]]|isbn=978-1-921171-26-0}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stjosephskpt.qld.edu.au/About%20Us/Pages/St-Joseph%27s-History.aspx|title=St Joseph's History|last=|first=|date=|website=St Joseph's Primary School|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109100645/http://www.stjosephskpt.qld.edu.au/About%20Us/Pages/St-Joseph's-History.aspx|archive-date=2019-11-09|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 1887, the [[Yungaba Immigration Centre]] was built on Main Street at Kangaroo Point to replace the poor facilities at the existing centre in [[William Street, Brisbane|William Street]].<ref name=\"yungaba\" />\n\nIn June 1888, six allotments, being subdivisions 1 to 6 of subdivisions 7 to 11 of portions 68 in the Parish of Kangaroo Point, on Walmsley Street between the Garden Point Ferry and Main Street were advertised to be auctioned for sale by Simon Fraser & Son.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article177865101|title=Advertising|date=19 June 1888|newspaper=[[Telegraph (Brisbane)|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=24 September 2019|issue=4,895|location=Queensland, Australia|page=8|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> A map advertising the auction contained a local sketch by the surveyors, Hamilton & Raff.<ref>{{Cite document|title=Choice allotments Walmsley Street, Kangaroo Point|last=|first=|date=23 June 1888|hdl = 10462/deriv/398712}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1928, 19 subdivisions adjacent to the Brisbane River and titled \"Town Reach River Sites\" were advertised to be auctioned for sale by Isles, Love & Co Limited. A map advertising the auction includes an aerial photograph and a panoramic photograph of the area.<ref>{{Cite document|title=Town Reach River sites|last=|first=|date=22 September 1928|hdl = 10462/deriv/258186}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article21350173|title=Advertising|date=1 September 1928|newspaper=[[The Brisbane Courier]]|accessdate=24 September 2019|issue=22,028|location=Queensland, Australia|page=28|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nFor many years the suburb was dominated by the factories of heavy engineering businesses, particularly those involved in the maritime industry, such as [[Evans Deakin and Company|Evans Deakin]], Buzzacott & Co and [[Evans, Anderson, Phelan & Co]]. Evans Deakin built the largest ship ever constructed on the Brisbane River, the 66,000 tonne oil tanker ''Robert Miller'', which became adrift in the river during the [[1974 Brisbane flood]].<ref name=\"b150s\">{{cite book|title=Brisbane 150 Stories|author=McBride, Frank|publisher=Brisbane City Council Publication|year=2009|isbn=978-1-876091-60-6|pages=250\u2013251|display-authors=etal}}</ref> The last vessel to be built by Evans Deakin was an oil rig called ''Southern Cross''. The company vacated the site in 1976,<ref name=\"b150s\" /> with it later being redeveloped for high-rise accommodation.\n\nStone was quarried from the cliffs and used as building material. Until the 1930s, Evans Anderson & Phelan built steam locomotives at their Kangaroo Point works for [[Queensland Rail]]ways, however their works were not located near a railway, so the completed locomotives were delivered along Main Street on temporary track.\n\nUntil the federation of the Australian colonies in 1901, the Queensland Navy's main storage facility was located in the suburb. The first ship-based radio transmission in Australia was made between [[HMQS Gayundah|HMAS ''Gayundah'']] and the buildings in 1903. The naval stores buildings were occupied by the [[Royal Australian Navy]] until 1959, and then by the [[Australian Army]] until 1984. The heritage-listed buildings are now used by an adventure company focussing on river activities and rock climbing.\n\nThe opening of the Story Bridge ({{Coord|-27.4693|153.0359|type:landmark_region:AU-QLD|display=|name=Story Bridge (Kangaroo Point end)}}) in July 1940 was the most significant development of the suburb. [[Trolleybuses in Brisbane|Trolleybuses]] operated by the [[Brisbane City Council]] linked the suburb with Fortitude Valley via the Story Bridge from 1953 to 1969, running along Main Street from Woolloongabba and other eastern suburbs.<ref>{{cite book|title=Brisbane's tramways: The last decade|author1=Clark, H.R.|author2=Keenan, D.R.|publisher=Transit Press|year=1977|isbn=978-0-909338-01-5}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 2% of sex workers in Queensland were street prostitutes operating in inner Brisbane suburbs such as Kangaroo Point.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pla.qld.gov.au/Resources/PLA/reportsPublications/documents/Select%20Sex%20Industry%20Statistics.pdf|title=Select Sex Industry Statistics|date=December 2011|website=www.pla.qld.gov.au/|publisher=Prostitution Licensing Authority|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190314172936/http://www.pla.qld.gov.au/Resources/PLA/reportsPublications/documents/Select%20Sex%20Industry%20Statistics.pdf|archive-date=14 March 2019|accessdate=30 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/questnews/southeast/calls-for-police-crackdown-on-prostitution-in-inner-brisbane-suburb/news-story/4c78d88535b8ec6f4ccac03d957c0acd|title=Prostitution crackdown: Calls for police to crackdown at inner Brisbane Suburb|date=3 May 2017|website=news.com.au|publisher=The Courier Mail|accessdate=30 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the {{CensusAU|2016}}, Kangaroo Point had a population of 8,063 people.<ref name=Census2016>{{Census 2016 AUS|id=SSC31496|name=Kangaroo Point (SSC)|accessdate=20 October 2018|quick=on}}</ref>\n\n==Attractions==\nKangaroo Point is a popular recreation spot, conveniently close to the city and the [[South Bank Parklands, Brisbane|South Bank Parklands]]. The [[Kangaroo Point Cliffs]], situated on the east bank of the city bend of the Brisbane River north of the Maritime Museum, opposite [[Riverstage]] and the [[Queensland University of Technology]] at [[Gardens Point, Brisbane|Gardens Point]]. The Look-out at Kangaroo Point is also included as one of the stops of [[Brisbane Transport]]'s City Sights bus service. Kangaroo Point is also home to one of less than 200 Mormon temples in the world {as of August 2015}. Kangaroo Point is also home to Ellis Street, one of the 20 steepest hills in Brisbane according to Brisbane City Council. Kangaroo Point is also home to the more-than-160-year-old St Mary's Anglican Church.\n\n[[File:Brisbane During Twilight.jpg|thumb|right|Brisbane's [[Brisbane central business district|CBD]] from Kangaroo Point cliffs]]\nThe cliffs are a popular picnic, [[rock climbing]] and [[abseiling]] site. The steepness of the cliffs was increased by quarrying operations which mined the [[volcanic rock]] or [[rhyolite]] [[lava]] flows which form the cliffs. The lava was deposited in the [[Triassic]] Period about 230 million years ago and filled up an ancient river valley. They currently form the banks of the Brisbane River.\n\nThe [[Story Bridge]] is a prominent landmark. It is able to be climbed with authorised tourist groups and provides the main means of access to the north of Brisbane. Directly under the bridge is the Story Bridge Hotel, and [[Yungaba Immigration Centre|Yungaba]], one of Brisbane's most unusual and iconic landmarks.<ref>[http://www.brisbane-australia.com/kangaroo-point.html Kangaroo Point] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022154508/http://www.brisbane-australia.com/kangaroo-point.html |date=22 October 2013 }} Brisbane Tourism Guide. Retrieved on 2013-11-07.</ref>\n\nThe ''Kangaroo Point Natural History Project'' was implemented by the council in 2013 to recognise the contribution by some of Queensland's pioneering scientists and researchers from the area. Along a heritage trail through the CT White and James Warner parks are a series of signs and sculptures to commemorate their lives and work: [[Cyril Tenison White]] (government botanist), [[Frederick Manson Bailey]] (colonial botanist), [[Silvester Diggles]] (naturalist), [[Oscar Werner Tiegs]] (entomologist and zoologist), [[James Warner (surveyor)|James Warner]] (surveyor), and [[Harry Oakman]] (landscape artist).<ref>{{cite web|title=Kangaroo Point Natural History Project|url=http://www.brisbane.qld.gov.au/facilities-recreation/sports-and-leisure/walking/walking-trails/heritage-trails/kangaroo-point-natural-history-project/index.htm|publisher=Brisbane City Council|accessdate=18 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219020826/http://www.brisbane.qld.gov.au/facilities-recreation/sports-and-leisure/walking/walking-trails/heritage-trails/kangaroo-point-natural-history-project/index.htm|archive-date=19 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Transport==\n[[Image:Kangaroo Point Cliffs.jpg|thumb|right|[[Kangaroo Point Cliffs]] after sunset]]\n[[File:Brisbane Lights at Night from Kangaroo Point.jpg|thumb|right|Walkway along the cliffs]]\nBy bus the suburb is serviced by the [[South East Busway]] transit line and buses along Main Street and Shafstons Avenue. By road Kangaroo Point residents rely on the [[Story Bridge]] and [[Captain Cook Bridge, Brisbane|Captain Cook Bridge]] for access to the north, and the [[Pacific Motorway (Brisbane-Ballina)|Southeast Freeway]] for access to the south. Main Street connects the Story Bridge through the suburb to the South East Freeway. Bicycle paths run along the [[Brisbane River]] from South Bank to and over the Story Bridge. The bicycle paths are heavily used by cyclists, roller skaters and pedestrians.\n\n[[Transdev Brisbane Ferries|CityFerry]] service from the [[Eagle Street Pier ferry wharf|Eagle Street Pier]] in the CBD and the [[Sydney Street ferry wharf|Sydney Street Pier]] in New Farm to [[Holman Street ferry wharf]] near the peak of Kangaroo Point, [[Thornton Street ferry wharf]] on the west side of the point, or [[Dockside ferry wharf]] on the east side. CityCat services do not directly service Kangaroo Point.<ref>[http://www.translink.com.au/qt/translin.nsf/ReferenceLookup/080804_map_network_ferry.pdf/$file/080804_map_network_ferry.pdf Translink Ferry Map] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720195740/http://www.translink.com.au/qt/translin.nsf/ReferenceLookup/080804_map_network_ferry.pdf/$file/080804_map_network_ferry.pdf |date=20 July 2008 }}.</ref>\n\nThe [[North South Bypass Tunnel|M7 Clem Jones Tunnel]], a toll tunnel, which opened in March 2010, has a connection on Shafston Avenue. It diverts some traffic travelling through the suburb while providing an additional transport route for residents.\n\nA green bridge was proposed in 2010 to the west to connect Kangaroo Point to Brisibane City and to the east to connect Kangaroo Point to Merthyr Road [[New Farm, Queensland|New Farm]], but at March 2020  these projects have not been progressed.<ref name=\"bcob\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/queensland/brisbane-city-of-bridges-20100322-qr4y.html |title=Brisbane, city of bridges? |accessdate=14 March 2013 |date=23 March 2010 |work=Brisbane Times |publisher=Fairfax Media |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110204103451/http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/queensland/brisbane-city-of-bridges-20100322-qr4y.html |archive-date=4 February 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Cross River Rail]] tunnel is planned to connect under Kangaroo Point Cliffs from Woolloongabba to an [[Albert Street, Brisbane|Albert Street]] railway station.\n\n==Demographics==\nIn the {{CensusAU|2011}} of Population and Housing, the population of Kangaroo Point postcode area was 7,000 people, in an area of 1.3 square kilometres.<ref name=\"census11\">{{Census 2011 AUS|id=SSC30845 |name=Kangaroo Point (State Suburb)|accessdate=14 March 2013 |quick=on}}</ref> The population was 48.3% females and 51.7% males. The median age of the Kangaroo Point population was 35 years of age, 2 years below the Australian median.  53.1% of people living in Kangaroo Point were born in Australia, compared to the national average of 69.8%; the next most common countries of birth were New Zealand 5.2%, England 4.4%, India 1.6%, Ireland 1.6%, Taiwan 1.2%.  69.6% of people spoke only English at home; the next most popular languages were 1.9% Mandarin, 1.8% Spanish, 0.9% Cantonese, 0.9% Nepali, 0.9% Italian. It has one of the city's highest proportion of residents living in flats, units or apartments (78.8%). Residents in stand alone houses make up only 16.6% of the population. 59.9% of residents are renters while only 18.7% fully own their dwelling. According to REIQ, the median house price in Kangaroo Point for the calendar year 2010 was $658,500.<ref>[http://reiq.com/Suburbs.aspx?su=Kangaroo%20Point&postcode=4169&type=1 Kangaroo Point]. REIQ Suburb profile. Retrieved 14 March 2013.</ref>\n\n==Education==\nSt Joseph's Primary School is a Catholic primary (Prep-6) school for boys and girls at 26-36 Leopard Street ({{coord|-27.4829|153.0329|type:edu_region:AU-QLD|name=St Joseph's Primary School}}).<ref name=\"SchoolList2018\">{{cite web|url=https://data.qld.gov.au/dataset/state-and-non-state-school-details/resource/5b39065c-df32-415c-994c-5ff12f8de997|title=State and non-state school details|date=9 July 2018|publisher=[[Queensland Government]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121065959/https://data.qld.gov.au/dataset/state-and-non-state-school-details/resource/5b39065c-df32-415c-994c-5ff12f8de997|archivedate=21 November 2018|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stjosephskpt.qld.edu.au|title=St Joseph's Primary School|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref> In 2017, the school had an enrolment of 318 students with 24 teachers (18 full-time equivalent) and 16 non-teaching staff (9 full-time equivalent).<ref name=\"ACARA2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acara.edu.au/docs/default-source/default-document-library/school-profile-20172c7b12404c94637ead88ff00003e0139.xlsx?sfvrsn=0|title=ACARA School Profile 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181122010027/http://www.acara.edu.au/docs/default-source/default-document-library/school-profile-20172c7b12404c94637ead88ff00003e0139.xlsx?sfvrsn=0|archivedate=22 November 2018|accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThere are no government schools in Kangaroo Point. The nearest government primary school is [[East Brisbane State School]] in [[East Brisbane, Queensland|East Brisbane]]. The nearest government secondary school is Coorparoo Secondary College in [[Coorparoo, Queensland|Coorparoo]].<ref name=\"globe\">{{Queensland Globe|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFor tertiary studies, Kangaroo Point is host to Shafston International College and the [[Aboriginal Centre for the Performing Arts (ACPA)]] (which has now moved to the Judith Wright Centre in Fortitude Valley) and was host to a Southbank Institute of TAFE campus until its demolition in 2009. Directly across the river from the cliffs is the [[Queensland University of Technology]] (Gardens Point campus) and in an adjacent suburb, the main campus for TAFE Queensland Brisbane (South Bank).\n\n==Heritage listings==\n[[File:Yungaba Immigration Centre riverside lawn.jpg|thumb|[[Yungaba Immigration Centre]] and riverside lawn, 2015]]\n[[File:St Nicholas Russian Orthodox Cathedral.jpg|thumb|[[St Nicholas Russian Orthodox Cathedral]], 2015]]\nKangaroo Point has a number of [[heritage-listed]] sites, including:\n* 34 Amesbury Street: former [[Naval Stores, Kangaroo Point|Naval Stores]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15014|Naval Stores (former)|600239|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 94 Baines Street: [[Raymond Park (West) Air Raid Shelter]]<ref>{{cite QHR|19599|Raymond Park (West) Air Raid Shelter|602478|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 23 Castlebar Street: [[Shafston House]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15016|Shafston House|600241|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 116 Holman Street: [[Holman Street ferry wharf|Holman Street Ferry Terminal]]<ref>{{cite QHR|19566|Holman Street Ferry Terminal|602445|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 9 Leopard Street: [[Lamb House, Kangaroo Point|Lamb House]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15017|Home|600242|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* Lower River Terrace: [[Kangaroo Point Cliffs]]<ref>{{cite QHR|19520|Kangaroo Point Cliffs|602400|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 76 Lower River Terrace: [[Cliffside Apartments]]<ref>{{cite QHR|16411|Cliffside Apartments|601650|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 102 Main Street: [[Yungaba Immigration Centre]]<ref name=yungaba>{{cite QHR|15020|Yungaba Immigration Depot|600245|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 255 Main Street: [[Sunnyside, Kangaroo Point|Sunnyside]]<ref>{{cite QHR|16547|Sunnyside|601810|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 261 - 267 Main Street: [[Silverwells]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15018|Silverwells|600243|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 433, 447 & 449 Main Street: [[St Mary's Anglican Church, Kangaroo Point|St Mary's Anglican Church]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15019|St Mary's Anglican Church|600244|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 2 Scott Street: [[Scott Street Flats]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15936|Scott Street Flats|601171|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 69 Shafston Avenue: [[Leckhampton, Kangaroo Point|Leckhampton]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15021|Leckhampton|600246|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 330-334B Vulture Street: [[St Nicholas Russian Orthodox Cathedral]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15133|St Nicholas Russian Orthodox Cathedral|600358|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 184 Wellington Road: [[Raymond Park (East) Air Raid Shelter]]<ref>{{cite QHR|19600|Raymond Park (East) Air Raid Shelter|602479|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==<!-- Please respect alphabetical order, only notable people (with an article or citations that demonstrate notability) -->\n* [[Frederick Manson Bailey]], Australian botanist\n* [[Peter Burge (cricketer)|Peter Burge]], Australian cricketer\n* [[James Davis (escaped convict)|James Davis]], convict and pioneer\n* [[Silvester Diggles]], Australian musician and ornithologist\n* [[Alec Hurwood]], Australian cricketer\n* [[John Lavarack]], A Former [[Governor of Queensland]]\n* [[Frank Payne (artist)|Frances Mallalieu Payne]] (1885-1976) artist and illustrator<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/payne-frances-mallalieu-frank-11354|title = Payne, Frances Mallalieu (Frank) (1885\u20131976)|date = 2000|accessdate = 30 March 2015|website = Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher = |last = Philp|first = Angela|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150403003634/http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/payne-frances-mallalieu-frank-11354|archive-date = 3 April 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n* [[Alfred John Raymond]], alderman for Kangaroo Point and mayor of Brisbane in 1912\n* [[Charles Jackson Stewart]], (1876-1954) hotel keeper at the Criterion Hotel, George Street<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/stewart-charles-jackson-11766|title=Stewart, Charles Jackson (1876\u20131954)|last=Cook|first=Margaret|date=2002|website=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=|accessdate=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402211049/http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/stewart-charles-jackson-11766|archive-date=2 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Oscar Werner Tiegs]], Australian zoologist\n* [[Cyril Tenison White]], Australian botanist\n* [[Christopher Wrench]], organist\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Kangaroo Point, Queensland}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://queenslandplaces.com.au/kangaroo-point|title=Kangaroo Point|publisher=Centre for the Government of Queensland, University of Queensland|website=Queensland Places}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191806/http://www.epa.qld.gov.au/projects/heritage/