{"title_page": "Murder of Marcia King", "text_new": "{{short description|Formerly unidentified murder victim}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Marcia King\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| image              = File:Marcia King.jpg\n| image_size         = 200px\n| alt                = \n| birth_name         = Marcia Lenore King\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1959|6|9}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Winsor|first1=Morgan|title=Body of 'Buckskin Girl' Found in Ohio in 1981 Identified as Arkansas Woman|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/body-buckskin-girl-found-ohio-1981-identified-arkansas/story?id=54417156|accessdate=April 13, 2018|work=[[American Broadcasting Company]]|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = \n| disappeared_date   = Circa 1980<!-- {{Disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) -->\n| disappeared_place  = [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]], [[Pulaski County, Arkansas|Pulaski County]], [[Arkansas]], U.S.<ref name=\"tdn\"/>\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1981|04|22|1959|06|09}} <ref name=namus/> <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = [[Troy, Ohio|Troy]], [[Miami County, Ohio|Miami County]], [[Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = [[Homicide]] by [[strangulation]]\n| body_discovered    = April 24, 1981\n| resting_place      = Riverside Cemetery, Troy, Miami County, Ohio\n| resting_place_coordinates = {{Coord|39.9660|N|84.3256|W|region:US-OH_type:landmark|display=inline}} (approximate) <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| parents            = Jonathan W. Sossoman\u2020 <br />Bonnie Bryant-King<ref name=\"penwell\">{{cite web |title=Jack W. Sossoman |url=https://www.penwellgabeltopeka.com/Obituary/152633/Jack-Sossoman/Topeka-Kansas |publisher=Penwell-Gabel Home Send Flowers |accessdate=30 August 2018 |date=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = Formerly unidentified victim of homicide\n| height             = {{height|ft=5|in=5|abbr=mos}} (approximate)\n| weight             = \n}}\n\n'''Marcia Lenore Sossoman (King)'''<!-- Use name that the family had inscribed on her gravestone --><ref name=\"sossoman\" /> ({{Birth date|1959|6|9}} \u2013 {{Death date|1981|04|22}}) was a 21-year-old [[Arkansas]] woman who was murdered in April 1981 and whose body was discovered in [[Troy, Ohio]] approximately forty-eight hours after her murder. Her body remained unidentified for 36 years before being identified via [[DNA analysis]] and [[genetic genealogy]] in April 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Buckskin Girl\" Case: DNA Breakthrough Leads to ID of 1981 Murder Victim|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/buckskin-girl-case-groundbreaking-dna-tech-leads-to-id-of-1981-murder-victim/|accessdate=April 13, 2018|work=Crimesider|agency=American Broadcasting Company|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> King was the first [[unidentified decedent]] to be identified via this method of [[Forensic science|forensic investigation]].<ref name=\"timeline\" /><ref name=\"miamiID\">{{cite news|title=Miami County Sheriff's Office Identifies 1981 Cold Case Victim|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/news/local/miami-county-sheriff-office-release-new-details-1981-unsolved-homicide-case/fmfdENjXMReEHV5VZGPcpI/|accessdate=April 11, 2018|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrior to her 2018 identification,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Spain|first1=Jamie|title=37 Years After Young Woman's Mysterious Slaying, She is Finally Identified|url=https://people.com/crime/buckskin-girl-found-dead-ohio-identified-37-year-later/|accessdate=March 22, 2020|work=People|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> King was informally known as \"'''Buckskin Girl'''\" and \"'''Miami County [[Jane Doe]]'''\". The first of these two names is in reference to the distinctive tasseled [[buckskin (leather)|buckskin]] poncho<ref>{{cite news|title=After 37 Years, Murder Victim Buckskin Girl Has Her Name Back|url=https://torontosun.com/news/world/crime-hunter-after-37-years-murder-victim-buckskin-girl-has-her-name-back|accessdate=March 26, 2020|date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> she was wearing at the time of her discovery.<ref name=doe>{{cite web|title=Case File 133UFOH|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/133ufoh.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name=help />\n\nFollowing the identification of her body, Marcia King's family erected a new headstone at her grave in Riverside Cemetery, inscribed with her actual name. The investigation into her murder is ongoing.<ref name=sossoman/>\n\n==Discovery==\nOn April 24, 1981, three members of the public discovered the body of a young [[Caucasian race|Caucasian]] woman in a ditch alongside Greenlee Road in [[Newton Township, Miami County, Ohio|Newton Township]], [[Troy, Ohio|Troy]], Ohio.<ref name=still>{{cite news|title=Victim Still Unidentified|url=http://www.officialcoldcaseinvestigations.com/attachment.php?attachmentid=1904&stc=1&d=1332268098|accessdate=September 29, 2015|date=April 30, 1981}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Neil|first1=Helen|title=Amateur Sleuths Restore Identity to the Dead|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Amateur-sleuths-restore-identity-to-the-dead-3219899.php|accessdate=July 23, 2015|work=Seattle Post Intelligencer|date=March 30, 2008}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|These members of the public had first noticed the decedent's deerskin poncho lying alongside Greenlee Road before discovering her body.<ref name=\"whio\" />}} The young woman was lying in a [[fetal position]], on her right side, and without shoes or socks.<ref name=\"tdn\" /><ref name=namus>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 4790|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/4790|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=7 November 2014|date=10 December 2008}}</ref> These members of the public called police to report their discovery.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Technology Being Used in 'Buckskin Girl' Case|url=https://codingsocieties.com/new-technology-being-used-in-buckskin-girl-case-troy-daily-news/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Autopsy===\nThe decedent's body was autopsied on the afternoon of her discovery. The medical examination revealed she had suffered extensive [[Blunt trauma|blunt force trauma]] to the head and neck,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mullen|first1=Shannon|title=Was Strangled 'Buckskin Girl' from New Jersey?|url=https://eu.app.com/story/news/crime/jersey-mayhem/cold-cases/2016/04/29/buckskin-girl-murder-pollen-nj/83707116/|accessdate=March 31, 2020|date=April 30, 2016}}</ref> before she had been strangled to death<ref name=still/> approximately forty-eight hours before her body was discovered.<ref>{{cite web|title=Buckskin Girl|url=https://dnadoeproject.org/case/buckskin-girl/|website=dnadoeproject.org|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> In addition, her liver had also been lacerated.<ref name=ramsey>{{cite news|last1=Ramsey|first1=Rachelle|title=Jane Doe Doesn't Have a Name or Suspect|url=http://www.officialcoldcaseinvestigations.com/attachment.php?attachmentid=1999&stc=1&d=1348637351|accessdate=September 29, 2015|date=August 29, 1994}}</ref><ref name=jim>{{cite news|last1=DeBrosse|first1=Jim|title='Somebody Cares About Them. We Do':Jane Doe Cases Could be Solved 'Overnight' if Database Utilized, Police Say|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/media/news155.html|accessdate=June 1, 2014|newspaper=Dayton Daily News|date=August 6, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe woman had been between {{cvt|5|ft|4|in|cm}} and {{cvt|5|ft|6|in|cm}} in height, aged between eighteen and twenty-six, and weighed {{convert|125|-|130|lb}}.<ref name=cause/><ref name=id/> She had naturally reddish-brown hair, which was braided into pigtails on both sides of her head.<ref name=doe/><ref name=help/><ref name=id/><ref name=cause>{{cite news|title=Strangulation Cause of Death|url=http://www.officialcoldcaseinvestigations.com/attachment.php?attachmentid=1897&stc=1&d=1332267864|accessdate=September 29, 2015|date=April 27, 1981}}</ref> Her eyes were light brown in color, and she had freckles across her face.<ref name=doe/> In addition, her nose was described as being \"very pointed\".<ref name=watch/> The victim also had a ruddy complexion, indicating she had spent a lot of time outdoors in the final weeks or months of her life.<ref name=doe /><ref name=tri/>\n\nThe young woman had maintained a high level of personal hygiene. All her teeth, including her [[Wisdom tooth|wisdom teeth]], were in good condition and had no evidence of [[Dental restoration|fillings]] or other dental work, except for one porcelain [[Crown (dentistry)|crown]] upon her upper-right [[incisor]].<ref name=namus/><ref name=BGNCMEC/> The coroner also noted several scars upon her body, including a vertical scar under the chin, with other scars visible upon one wrist, both arms and one ankle.<ref name=oh/><ref name=miami>{{cite web |title=Miami Ohio Jane Doe April 1981 |url=http://canyouidentifyme.org/MiamiCountyJaneDoeApril1981 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210190938/http://canyouidentifyme.org/MiamiCountyJaneDoeApril1981 |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 10, 2013 |accessdate=April 13, 2014 |year=2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Clothing===\nThe young woman was dressed in blue bell-bottom [[Wrangler (jeans)|Wrangler]] jeans, a brown turtleneck pullover sweater with an orange crisscross design on the front, a white size 32D bra,<ref name=doe/> and a hoodless deerskin poncho with purple lining, which appeared to be handmade.<ref name=tri>{{cite web|title=Miami County Jane Doe, OH |url=http://meyahna.tripod.com/pg21.html |accessdate=April 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414175922/http://meyahna.tripod.com/pg21.html |archivedate=April 14, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=help>{{cite web|last=Besso |first=Donna |title=Need Help Identifying \"The Buckskin Girl\" |url=http://www.gather.com/viewArticle.action?articleId=281474977406629 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414195811/http://www.gather.com/viewArticle.action?articleId=281474977406629 |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 14, 2014 |accessdate=April 13, 2014 |date=July 25, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=oh>{{cite web|title=Ohio Unsolved Homicides|url=http://www.ohioattorneygeneral.gov/Files/Law-Enforcement/Investigator/Unidentified-Remains|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref> She wore no shoes or socks.<ref name=id>{{cite web|title=Miami Ohio Jane Doe April 1981|url=http://canyouidentifyme.org/MiamiOhioJaneDoeApril1981|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref> No form of identification was located upon her body or at the crime scene.<ref name=oh/><ref name=miami/>\n\n==Initial investigation==\nThe dental charts and fingerprints of this decedent yielded no results matching her to any known missing person, and her fingerprints matched no local police records, indicating she had no criminal record.<ref>{{cite news|title=Buckskin Girl Press Release|url=https://dnadoeproject.org/press-release-for-buckskin-girl/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=pril 11, 2018}}</ref> Early police efforts to identify this decedent also involved the creation of a sketch of the face that was published in local newspapers and broadcast on television networks on April 28, 1981.<ref name=no>{{cite news|title=No identification Yet|url=http://www.officialcoldcaseinvestigations.com/attachment.php?attachmentid=1898&stc=1&d=1332267912|accessdate=September 29, 2015|date=April 28, 1981}}</ref> Initial media publicity surrounding the murder generated approximately two hundred leads. Although all were investigated, all failed to bear fruition.<ref name=still/>\n\nThe victim gradually became known as \"Buckskin Girl\" in reference to the distinctive tasseled buckskin jacket she was wearing when found.<ref name=doe>{{cite web|title=Case File 133UFOH|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/133ufoh.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name=help /><ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Neill|first1=Helen|title=Volunteers Use Computers to Name the Dead|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/tech/news/2008-03-29-naming-dead_N.htm|accessdate=July 23, 2015|work=USA Today|publisher=Associated Press|date=March 30, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAuthorities strongly believed Buckskin Girl had been murdered elsewhere and her body discarded beside the road shortly after her death.<ref name=no/><ref name=cause/> This conclusion was supported by the fact her bare feet were clean, showing no indication of her having walked on dirt, and because [[Interstate 75]] is just {{convert|5|mi|0|spell=in}} from where her body was recovered, making the site a convenient and discreet location to discard a body.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://triblive.com/news/projects/ourstories/10570633-74/doe-jane-hickey|title=Slain Jane Doe's Curious Case in Ohio Still Puzzles After 35 Years|first=Chris|last=Togneri|date=June 4, 2016|website=TribLIVE.com}}</ref> Police and the media later speculated that she may have been a teenage runaway or a possible victim of a serial killer, who murdered multiple sex workers in the region during the 1980s and 1990s.<ref name=jim/><ref name=doe/><ref name=tri/> But the scene and her body showed no signs of sexual assault, rape or other sexual activity, indicating she was unlikely to have been a sex worker.<ref name=doe/> Because of the absence of footwear, some believe she may have been murdered by an abusive significant other.<ref name=watch>{{cite web | url=http://crimewatchdaily.com/2015/10/19/help-crime-watch-daily-and-carl-koppelman-give-names-to-these-5-murder-victims/ | title=Help Crime Watch Daily and Carl Koppelman Give Names to These 5 Murder Victims | publisher=Fox | work=Crime Watch Daily | date=October 10, 2015 | accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> A retired investigator is also known to have opined his belief the decedent was unlikely to be from the area where she was discovered.<ref name=\"whio\" />\n\nThe investigation into Buckskin Girl's murder gradually became a [[cold case]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Winsor|first1=Morgan|title=Jane Doe No More: Miami County Sheriff IDs Cold Case Victim 37 Years Later|url=https://www.whio.com/news/local/miami-county-sheriff-office-release-new-details-1981-unsolved-homicide-case/fmfdENjXMReEHV5VZGPcpI/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|work=[[WHIO-TV]]|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref> although police and other officials continued to investigate her murder. Her clothing and other [[physical evidence]] recovered at the crime scene was retained, and a sample of her blood preserved.<ref name=\"whio\">{{cite news|title=Miami County Authorities Still Working on Jane Doe Case|url=http://www.whio.com/videos/news/miami-county-authorities-still-working-on-jane-doe/vDQhjj/|accessdate=March 29, 2016|work=WHIO|publisher=Cox Media Group|date=April 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425044702/http://www.whio.com/videos/news/miami-county-authorities-still-working-on-jane-doe/vDQhjj/|archive-date=April 25, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Theories==\n===Lifestyle===\nInvestigators theorized that Buckskin Girl had been a runaway teenager, a foster child, or a transient wanderer who had not spent a significant period of time in Ohio prior to her death, although her high quality of personal hygiene strongly indicated that she had not lived as a vagrant.<ref name=doe/> As her body was located close to a town road instead of a highway, the probability of her being a wanderer for a significant amount of time was considered to be negligible.<ref name=watch/> Nonetheless, the failure to establish her identity hindered investigators' efforts to solve her murder. As her identity remained undiscovered, investigating authorities came to increasingly believe the reason Buckskin Girl remained unidentified had been due to the fact that she had been murdered far from her hometown.<ref name=\"perspectives\" />\n\nA 2016 [[isotope analysis]] of the decedent's hair and fingernails revealed Buckskin Girl had spent approximately four months in areas within the [[Southwestern United States|Southwestern]] and/or [[Southeastern United States|Southeastern]] United States, as opposed to Ohio, prior to her murder, although the forensic palynology tests had revealed she had most likely originated from either the Northeastern United States or [[Canada]], or had spent a significant amount of time inn these regions in the year prior to her murder.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 133UFOH|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/133ufoh.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vallieu\">{{cite news|last1=Vallieu|first1=Melody|title='Buckskin Girl' Not From Ohio|url=http://www.tdn-net.com/news/12204/buckskin-girl-not-from-ohio-2|accessdate=January 28, 2018|work=WDTN|agency=Troy Daily News|date=July 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hollenhorst|first1=John|title=Utah Firm Makes Breakthrough in 1981 Ohio Murder Case|url=https://www.ksl.com/?sid=40545046&nid=148&title=utah-firm-makes-breakthrough-in-1981-ohio-murder-case|accessdate=January 28, 2018|work=KSL|date=July 6, 2016}}</ref>\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| header = \n| width     =\n<!-- Image 1 -->\n| image1    = Buckskin Girl.jpg\n| width1    = 120\n| alt1      = \n| caption1  = 2011 [[forensic facial reconstruction]] of Buckskin Girl, depicting her distinctive braided hair.\n<!-- Image 2 -->\n| image2    = Photorealistic reconstruction of Buckskin girl .jpg\n| width2    = 120\n| alt2      = \n| caption2  = Additional facial reconstruction of Buckskin Girl, created prior to her 2018 identification as Marcia Lenore King.\n}}\n\n===Link to other murders===\nInitially, investigators speculated to a potential connection between this decedent and the murder of a 27-year-old woman two months earlier, in February 1981, although police never officially linked these two murders.<ref name=no/>\n\nIn 1985, police temporarily believed that Buckskin Girl had been a victim of a series of murders of sex workers and [[erotic dance]]rs in the area known as the [[Redhead murders|Redhead Murders]]. However, this theory was eventually disproven.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Aldrich|first1=Marta W.|title=Officials Puzzle Over String of Redhead Murders|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1985/Officials-Puzzle-Over-String-of-Redhead-Murders/id-8ad8d3ad5b164d3818827a4768931a2c|accessdate=April 16, 2015|work=Associated Press|date=April 25, 1985|location=Nashville, Tennessee}}</ref>\n\nSome investigators speculate that King was the first of numerous victims killed by an unidentified serial killer who perpetrated his known murders in the 1980s and 1990s, continuing until 2004, in Ohio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.websleuths.com/forums/attachment.php?attachmentid=33483&stc=1&d=1367899621|title=Still No Answers|work=The Blade|year=2004}}</ref> Such a serial killer was suspected to have killed approximately seven to ten other women, presumed sex workers and dancers, in Ohio.<ref name=uns/><ref name=pb91>{{cite news|title=Investigators of 10 Killings to Meet|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19910315&id=goQcAAAAIBAJ&pg=5900,7506894|accessdate=April 16, 2015|work=The Pittsburgh Press|date=March 15, 1991}}</ref> In 1991, a press conference preceded the creation of a task force that attempted to connect various murders in Ohio, New York, Pennsylvania and Illinois.<ref name=pb91/> These cases were originally linked by a reporter who discovered similarities among several unsolved murders in the area.<ref name=uns/>\n\nOn an episode of ''[[Unsolved Mysteries]],'' the Buckskin Girl case was briefly described, along with several other cases connected to the unidentified serial killer.<ref name=doe/> The program connected this case with the murders of Shirley Dee Taylor, Anna Marie Patterson, Hebron Jane Doe (identified in 2017 as [[Patrice Corley]])<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sneed|first1=Rob|title=Licking County Sheriff Identifies Jane Doe in 1990 Homicide Case|url=http://nbc4i.com/2017/08/30/licking-county-sheriff-identifies-jane-doe-in-1990-homicide-victim/|accessdate=September 26, 2017|date=August 30, 2017}}</ref> and other murder cases. All the victims had been beaten or strangled and had some clothing or jewelry missing. King was found without jewelry or footwear, and was killed in a manner similar to that of the other victims.<ref name=uns>{{cite web|title=Prostitute Serial Killer|url=http://unsolved.com/archives/prostitute-serial-killer|website=unsolved.com|publisher=[[Unsolved Mysteries]]|accessdate=April 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSeveral elements of evidence were found to contradict this theory. There was no indication Buckskin Girl had engaged in any form of sexual activity prior to her death.<ref name=doe/><ref name=uns/> In addition, unlike many of the victims of this serial killer, she was markedly well-groomed, with a history of dental care.<ref name=uns/><ref name=pb91/>\n\nIn 1987, police theorized that the women who may have been victims of the serial killer could have met with a man at a truck stop while working as sex workers. In the case of Anna Marie Patterson, there was a suspect, identified over a [[CB radio]] as \"Dr. No\", believed to be between the ages of 25 and 40.<ref name=uns/><ref name=sought/> Patterson's husband, who was involved with her work as a sex worker, said that she was uncomfortable accepting the man's requests. Other local sex workers, some speaking over the radio, had also said that they were suspicious of the man and did not want to take his trade. Police have suspected that this person may have been Patterson's killer, and that he may also have been involved in King's murder.<ref name=sought>{{cite news|title=Mysterious 'Dr. No\" Sought in Ohio Truck Stop Prostitute Murder|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19870419&id=gZMcAAAAIBAJ&pg=6860,829029|accessdate=April 16, 2015|work=The Pittsburgh Press|date=April 19, 1987}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, an Arizona man was linked to a series of rapes and murders in the Ohio area that occurred in the 1990s. Investigators in the Patrice Corley case, however, do not believe he was responsible for her murder.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sumner |first1=Michaela |title=County Prosecutor Doesn't Believe Arizona Man Connected to 1990 Patrice Corley Homicide |url=https://www.newarkadvocate.com/story/news/local/2019/02/18/county-prosecutor-doesnt-believe-arizona-man-tied-1990-homicide/2904061002/ |accessdate=February 20, 2019 |work=The Newark Advocate |date=February 18, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Ongoing investigation==\n===Further forensic analysis===\nBecause the decedent's body was found approximately forty-eight hours after her death,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mullen |first1=Shannon |title=Was Strangled 'Buckskin Girl' from New Jersey? |url=https://eu.app.com/story/news/crime/jersey-mayhem/cold-cases/2016/04/29/buckskin-girl-murder-pollen-nj/83707116 |accessdate=March 27, 2020|publisher=USA Today |date=April 30, 2016}}</ref> police were able to obtain her fingerprints, dental information, and a [[Genetic testing|DNA sample]].<ref name=namus/> With the increasing use of DNA analysis in criminal investigations, the case benefited by her DNA being added to the growing number of law enforcement databases.<ref name=\"whio\" />\n\nIn 2001, the Miami Valley Regional Crime Laboratory generated a [[DNA profiling|DNA profile]] of Buckskin Girl,<ref name=\"sossoman\" /> this data was entered into the newly established [[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]] (NamUs) database in 2008, through which her fingerprints, dental and DNA information were made nationally accessible to law enforcement.<ref name=\"perspectives\">{{cite book|title=New Perspectives in Forensic Human Skeletal Identification|editor1=Krista E. Latham|editor2=Eric J. Bartelink|editor3=Michael Finnegan|date=July 28, 2017|publisher=Elsevier, Inc.|isbn=978-0-12-805429-1|pages=124\u2013125|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jhdHDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA124&lpg=PA124&sig=AUEKTXjtDwA-hpSQptDTfynNu68&ved=0ahUKEwj_k5zNw6bXAhVMwWMKHXCwBxwQ6AEIQjAF#v=onepage&q=NamUS%3A%204790|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref> This data was able to concludsively rule out any possibility of 226 missing teenage girls and young women as Buckskin Girl.<ref name=namus/> In 2009, a [[mitochondrial DNA]] sample was submitted to the [[FBI]] for inclusion within the [[Combined DNA Index System]] (CODIS).<ref>{{cite news|title=Buckskin Girl Press Release|url=https://dnadoeproject.org/press-release-for-buckskin-girl/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=pril 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe following year, NamUs case management was assigned to Dr Elizabeth Murray, a [[Cincinnati]] based [[Forensic anthropology|forensic anthropologist]] and professor of biology, who remained involved with the case.<ref name=\"sossoman\" />\n[[File:Buckskin Girl NCMEC.jpg|150px|thumb|upright|[[Forensic facial reconstruction]] of Buckskin Girl, created by the [[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]]]\n\n===Facial reconstruction===\nIn April 2016, the [[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]] released an updated [[forensic facial reconstruction]] of the victim and added her case to their website, depicting her with and without her braided pigtails.<ref name=\"BGNCMEC\">{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1981|url=http://missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1107106/|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]]|accessdate=February 12, 2016|date=February 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Pollen analysis===\nIn 2016, the Miami County Police Department approved [[forensic palynology]] testing upon the victim's clothing in their efforts to identify her and her murderer(s). This testing was conducted by the [[United States Border Patrol|U.S. Customs and Border Protection Agency]].<ref name=\"vallieu\"/> The results of this testing suggested Buckskin Girl had either originated within the [[Northeastern United States|Northeastern]] United States, or had spent a significant amount of time in this region in the year prior to her murder. Her clothing also contained high levels of soot from exposure to vehicular traffic and/or industrial activity, supporting investigators' initial suspicions she may have been a habitual hitchhiker.<ref name=\"kennedy\">{{cite news|last1=Kennedy|first1=Megan|title=Miami Co. Cold Case Heats Up With Facial Reconstruction, Other developments|url=http://wdtn.com/2016/04/27/miami-co-cold-case-heats-up-with-facial-reconstruction-other-developments/|accessdate=April 28, 2016|work=WDTN News|agency=LIN Television Corporation|publisher=Media General|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref> In addition, the pollen<ref>{{cite news|last1=Norman|first1=Greg|title='Buckskin Girl' Identified After Being Found Dead in Ohio 37 Years Ago|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/buckskin-girl-identified-after-being-found-dead-in-ohio-37-years-ago|accessdate=April 2, 2020|work=Fox News|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> recovered from her external clothing suggested that, shortly before her murder, she had been in an arid climate such as the [[Western United States|Western]] United States, or northern [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Baker|first=Steve|title=New Developments Could ID 'Jane Doe' Found Dead 35 Years Ago|url=http://www.whio.com/videos/news/new-developments-could-id-jane-doe-found-dead-35/vDqjK2/|accessdate=April 28, 2016|work=WHIO|publisher=Cox Media Group|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Identification==\nOn April 9, 2018, the Miami Valley Crime Laboratory announced they had identified the decedent as 21-year-old Marcia Lenore King of [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]], [[Arkansas]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=\"Buckskin Girl\" Case: DNA Breakthrough Leads to ID of 1981 Murder Victim|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/buckskin-girl-case-groundbreaking-dna-tech-leads-to-id-of-1981-murder-victim/|accessdate=April 13, 2018|work=Crimesider|agency=American Broadcasting Company|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> Her identification had been achieved via [[Genetic testing|DNA analysis]] conducted by the [[DNA Doe Project]], with assistance from the Miami Valley Regional Crime Laboratory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forensicmag.com/news/2018/04/buck-skin-girl-case-break-success-new-dna-doe-project|title='Buck Skin Girl' Case Break is Success of New DNA Doe Project|date=April 16, 2018|publisher=Forensic Magazine|author=Seth Augenstein}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/611048/the-brave-new-world-of-genetic-genealogy/|title=The Brave New World of Genetic Genealogy|first=Debbie|last=Kennett|work=MIT Technology Review|date=April 28, 2018}}</ref> This organization was able to successfully match King's DNA to a sample submitted for comparison by a first cousin.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/04/golden-state-killer-east-area-rapist-dna-genealogy/559070/|title=How a Genealogy Website Led to the Alleged Golden State Killer|first=Sarah|last=Zhang|date=April 27, 2018|accessdate=March 29, 2020|work=[[The Atlantic]]}}</ref>\n\nKing had last been seen by her family in 1980. She had never officially been reported as a [[missing person]], although her family had continued to search for her.<ref name=\"tdn\">{{cite news|last1=Vallieu|first1=Melody|title='Buckskin Girl' Identified|url=http://www.tdn-net.com/top-stories/39213/buckskin-girl-identified|accessdate=April 12, 2018|work=Troy Daily News|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref> It is believed King had hitchhiked as the primary means of transportation, as investigators had theorized prior to her identification. She is also known to have had ties with both the [[Pittsburg, Kentucky|Pittsburg]] and [[Louisville, Kentucky]] districts.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jane 'Buckskin Girl' Doe Identified After 37 Years|url=https://www.fox19.com/story/37935396/jane-buckskin-girl-doe-identified-after-37-years/|work=[[Fox 19]]|accessdate=March 28, 2020|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|In the hope her daughter would initiate contact, King's mother had both continued to reside at the same house she lived in at the time of her daughter's disappearance, and kept the same phone number, should her daughter either return home or telephone her.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Dana|title=Cold Case Homicide Victim Identified after 37 Years|url=http://www.wdtn.com/news/local-news/cold-case-homicide-victim-identified-after-37-years/1116096993|work=WTDN 2|accessdate=April 13, 2018|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nAddressing the media to announce the formal identification of Buckskin Girl, a spokesman for the Miami County Police Department informed all present: \"Law enforcement never forgets. We've had a long journey to [be] where we are today.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eustachewich|first1=Lia|title=Murdered 'Buckskin Girl' Finally Identified 37 Years Later |url=https://nypost.com/2018/04/12/murdered-buckskin-girl-finally-identified-37-years-later/|work=The New York Post|accessdate=April 1, 2020|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> This spokesman also emphasized the investigation into King's homicide is ongoing.<ref name=\"miamiID\"/>\n\n===Ongoing investigation===\nIn July 2018, the Miami County Police Department announced they had received further information regarding King's actual whereabouts shortly prior to her death. This information included eyewitness accounts placing her in Louisville, Kentucky, approximately 14 days before her death.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.whio.com/news/local/buckskin-girl-grave-troy-get-new-headstone-with-her-name/nNQOsP1P8P4v40J6byXJvN/|title=Gravesite for 'Buckskin Girl': Gets New Headstone With Her Name|date=July 20, 2018|author=Nancy Bowman|work=whiotv}}</ref> Six eyewitnesses have also [[Corroborating evidence|corroborated]] accounts of King also being in Arkansas shortly before her murder. It is belieleived the reason she had traveled to Ohio may have been due to her suspected involvement with a religious organization.<ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite news |last1=Thomason |first1=Tyler |title=Ohio Cold Case Develops New Timeline, Puts Murder Victim in Arkansas Two Weeks Before Death |url=https://www.fox16.com/news/top-stories/ohio-cold-case-develops-new-timeline-puts-murder-victim-in-arkansas-two-weeks-before-death/1915607781 |accessdate=June 9, 2019 |work=FOX16 |date=April 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, the Miami County Sheriff's Office announced they had been able to further reconstruct King's whereabouts, and relationships, in the two weeks prior to her murder,<ref>{{cite news|title=Forensic Genealogy to Be Used in Miami County Unsolved Homicides|url=https://www.whio.com/news/local/forensic-genealogy-used-miami-county-unsolved-homicides/oAl1az1NfGHbopAT29pW3M/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|work=WHIO|date=February 13, 2020}}</ref> adding that as advances in technology now mean [[Nuclear DNA]] samples can be retrieved from hair samples missing the actual [[hair#Root of the hair|root]], they remained confident hair samples discovered at the crime scene and submitted to a renowned Californian [[Paleogenetics|paleogeneticist]] could yield a Nuclear DNA profile of either her murderer, ar an individual she had been in the company of very shortly before her death.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Technology Being Used in 'Buckskin Girl' Case|url=https://codingsocieties.com/new-technology-being-used-in-buckskin-girl-case-troy-daily-news/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=February 22, 2020}}</ref> Addressing these latest developments, Miami County Sheriff Dave Duchalk stated: \"We always have hopes to bring justice for homicide victims and their families. We never have, nor will we ever forget, and will continually work the case and, as new technologies are developed, will review our evidence to learn if it is worth re-submitting.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=New Technology Being Used in 'Buckskin Girl' Case|url=https://www.tdn-net.com/news/79673/new-technology-being-used-in-buckskin-girl-case|accessdate=March 26, 2020|date=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n{{quote box\n| quote = \"They were hopeful Marcia was going to come home. However, they are learning at this date that that's not going to happen.\"\n| source = [[Miami County, Ohio|Miami County]] Sheriff Steve Lord, addressing the media to announce the formal identification of Buckskin Girl. April 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=After 37 Years, Murder Victim Buckskin Girl Has Her Name Back|url=https://torontosun.com/news/world/crime-hunter-after-37-years-murder-victim-buckskin-girl-has-her-name-back|accessdate=March 26, 2020|date=April 14, 2018}}</ref>\n| width = 30em\n}}\n\n==Funeral==\nKing had been buried as a Jane Doe at Riverside Cemetery in Miami County weeks after her death, with several officers assigned to investigate her murder serving as [[pallbearer]]s at her funeral.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mullen |first1=Shannon |title=Was Strangled 'Buckskin Girl' from New Jersey? |url=https://eu.app.com/story/news/crime/jersey-mayhem/cold-cases/2016/04/29/buckskin-girl-murder-pollen-nj/83707116 |accessdate=March 27, 2020|publisher=USA Today |date=April 30, 2016}}</ref> Following the identification of her body, King's family chose for her to remain buried within this cemetery, with her stepmother, Cindy Sossoman, explaining her family's belief that, had it been God's plan that their daughter was to be murdered and to remain unidentified for so long, they believed King was [[Blessing|blessed]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ullery |first1=Michael |title=Sossoman Given Back Her Name |url=https://www.tdn-net.com/news/44910/sossoman-given-back-her-name |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Troy Daily News |publisher=AIM Media Midwest |date=July 20, 2018}}</ref> to have passed away within a community which had shown such consideration and dignity to her while she had remained unidentified.<ref name=sossoman/> Her parents had long since divorced, and her father, John Wesley Sossoman, had remarried, having several children with his second wife, all of whom had long wondered as to King's whereabouts and welfare.<ref name=sossoman/>\n\nOn July 20, 2018, a memorial service for King was held at a local chapel. This service was officiated by the Reverend Gregory Simmons. Her new headstone was unveiled at this service.<ref name=sossoman>{{cite news |last1=Ullery |first1=Michael |title=Sossoman Given Back Her Name |url=https://www.tdn-net.com/news/44910/sossoman-given-back-her-name |accessdate=July 24, 2018 |work=Troy Daily News |publisher=AIM Media Midwest |date=July 20, 2018}}</ref> Marcia's father, John, had died on January 5, 2018. Her brother, Daniel King, and half-brother, Jonathan Sossoman, had also died by the time of King's identity being discovered.<ref name=\"penwell\" /> Her stepmother and eight other surviving family members replaced the headstone simply reading \"Jane Doe\" with a headstone bearing her actual name at this service, which was attended by over fifty local residents. Describing King's personality, her stepmother described her as a \"very trusting\" young woman, before informing all present: \"Words don't describe the feelings we have for all of you, how you have loved her and taken her in your arms.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bowman |first1=Nancy |title=Gravesite for 'Buckskin Girl' Gets New Headstone with Her Name |url=https://www.springfieldnewssun.com/news/local/buckskin-girl-grave-troy-get-new-headstone-with-her-name/nNQOsP1P8P4v40J6byXJvN/ |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |publisher=Springfield News-Sun |date=July 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Cold case]]\n* [[Crime in Ohio]]\n* [[List of formerly unidentified decedents]]\n{{col-break}}\n* [[The Doe Network]]\n* [[Unidentified decedent]]\n* [[List of solved missing persons cases]]\n* [[List of unsolved deaths|Unsolved murders]]\n{{col-end}}\n{{Portal bar|1980s|Law|Ohio}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Cited works and further reading==\n* {{cite book| last = Halber| first = Deborah| title = The Skeleton Crew: How Amateur Sleuths Are Solving America's Coldest Cases| year = 2015| publisher = Simon & Schuster | location = New York| isbn = 978-1-451-65758-6}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Katz|first=H\u00e9l\u00e8na|title=Cold Cases: Famous Unsolved Mysteries, Crimes, and Disappearances in America|year=2010|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|location=Santa Barbara|isbn=978-0-313-37692-4}}\n* {{cite book| last = Murray| first = Elizabeth A.| title = Forensic Identification: Putting a Name and Face on Death| year = 2012| publisher = Twenty-First Century Books | location = Minneapolis| isbn = 978-1-467-70139-6}}\n* {{cite book| last = Newton| first = Michael| title = The Encyclopedia of Unsolved Crimes| year = 2004| publisher = Facts on File | location = New York| isbn = 978-0-816-07818-9}}\n* {{cite book| last = Pettem| first = Silvia| title = The Long Term Missing: Hope and Help for Families| year = 2017| publisher = Rowman & Littlefield | location = Maryland| isbn = 978-1-442-25680-4}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Shoester|first=Maria|title=Forensics in Law Enforcement|year=2006|publisher=[[Nova Science Publishers, Inc.]]|location=New York|isbn=978-1-600-21164-5}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Marcia King}}\n* [https://www.whio.com/news/crime--law/with-buckskin-girl-investigation-intensifies-into-unsolved-homicide/Fz5capsVOPZknmNAxuYDCP/ Contemporary news article] pertaining to the 2018 forensic identification of Buckskin Girl\n* [[DNA Doe Project]] [https://dnadoeproject.org/case/buckskin-girl/ ''webpage''] pertaining to the identification of Buckskin Girl\n* {{Find a Grave|124674061|Marcia King}}\n\n{{Unidentified decedent}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King, Marcia}}\n[[Category:1980s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:1981 in Ohio]]\n[[Category:1981 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by beating in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by strangulation in the United States]]\n[[Category:Female murder victims]]\n[[Category:Forensic palynology]]\n[[Category:Incidents of violence against women]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Unsolved murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Formerly unidentified murder victim}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Marcia King\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| image              = File:Marcia King.jpg\n| image_size         = 200px\n| alt                = \n| birth_name         = Marcia Lenore King\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1959|6|9}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Winsor|first1=Morgan|title=Body of 'Buckskin Girl' Found in Ohio in 1981 Identified as Arkansas Woman|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/body-buckskin-girl-found-ohio-1981-identified-arkansas/story?id=54417156|accessdate=April 13, 2018|work=[[American Broadcasting Company]]|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = \n| disappeared_date   = Circa 1980<!-- {{Disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) -->\n| disappeared_place  = [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]], [[Pulaski County, Arkansas|Pulaski County]], [[Arkansas]], U.S.<ref name=\"tdn\"/>\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1981|04|22|1959|06|09}} <ref name=namus/> <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = [[Troy, Ohio|Troy]], [[Miami County, Ohio|Miami County]], [[Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = [[Homicide]] by [[strangulation]]\n| body_discovered    = April 24, 1981\n| resting_place      = Riverside Cemetery, Troy, Miami County, Ohio\n| resting_place_coordinates = {{Coord|39.9660|N|84.3256|W|region:US-OH_type:landmark|display=inline}} (approximate) <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| parents            = Jonathan W. Sossoman\u2020 <br />Bonnie Bryant-King<ref name=\"penwell\">{{cite web |title=Jack W. Sossoman |url=https://www.penwellgabeltopeka.com/Obituary/152633/Jack-Sossoman/Topeka-Kansas |publisher=Penwell-Gabel Home Send Flowers |accessdate=30 August 2018 |date=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = Formerly unidentified victim of homicide\n| height             = {{height|ft=5|in=5|abbr=mos}} (approximate)\n| weight             = \n}}\n\n'''Marcia Lenore Sossoman (King)'''<!-- Use name that the family had inscribed on her gravestone --><ref name=\"sossoman\" /> ({{Birth date|1959|6|9}} \u2013 {{Death date|1981|04|22}}) was a 21-year-old [[Arkansas]] woman who was murdered in April 1981 and whose body was discovered in [[Troy, Ohio]] approximately forty-eight hours after her murder. Her body remained unidentified for 36 years before being identified via [[DNA analysis]] and [[genetic genealogy]] in April 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Buckskin Girl\" Case: DNA Breakthrough Leads to ID of 1981 Murder Victim|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/buckskin-girl-case-groundbreaking-dna-tech-leads-to-id-of-1981-murder-victim/|accessdate=April 13, 2018|work=Crimesider|agency=American Broadcasting Company|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> King was the first [[unidentified decedent]] to be identified via this method of [[Forensic science|forensic investigation]].<ref name=\"timeline\" /><ref name=\"miamiID\">{{cite news|title=Miami County Sheriff's Office Identifies 1981 Cold Case Victim|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/news/local/miami-county-sheriff-office-release-new-details-1981-unsolved-homicide-case/fmfdENjXMReEHV5VZGPcpI/|accessdate=April 11, 2018|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrior to her 2018 identification,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Spain|first1=Jamie|title=37 Years After Young Woman's Mysterious Slaying, She is Finally Identified|url=https://people.com/crime/buckskin-girl-found-dead-ohio-identified-37-year-later/|accessdate=March 22, 2020|work=People|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> King was informally known as \"'''Buckskin Girl'''\" and \"'''Miami County [[Jane Doe]]'''\". The first of these two names is in reference to the distinctive tasseled [[buckskin (leather)|buckskin]] poncho<ref>{{cite news|title=After 37 Years, Murder Victim Buckskin Girl Has Her Name Back|url=https://torontosun.com/news/world/crime-hunter-after-37-years-murder-victim-buckskin-girl-has-her-name-back|accessdate=March 26, 2020|date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> she was wearing at the time of her discovery.<ref name=doe>{{cite web|title=Case File 133UFOH|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/133ufoh.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name=help />\n\nFollowing the identification of her body, Marcia King's family erected a new headstone at her grave in Riverside Cemetery, inscribed with her actual name. The investigation into her murder is ongoing.<ref name=sossoman/>\n\n==Discovery==\nOn April 24, 1981, three members of the public discovered the body of a young [[Caucasian race|Caucasian]] woman in a ditch alongside Greenlee Road in [[Newton Township, Miami County, Ohio|Newton Township]], [[Troy, Ohio|Troy]], Ohio.<ref name=still>{{cite news|title=Victim Still Unidentified|url=http://www.officialcoldcaseinvestigations.com/attachment.php?attachmentid=1904&stc=1&d=1332268098|accessdate=September 29, 2015|date=April 30, 1981}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Neil|first1=Helen|title=Amateur Sleuths Restore Identity to the Dead|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Amateur-sleuths-restore-identity-to-the-dead-3219899.php|accessdate=July 23, 2015|work=Seattle Post Intelligencer|date=March 30, 2008}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|These members of the public had first noticed the decedent's deerskin poncho lying alongside Greenlee Road before discovering her body.<ref name=\"whio\" />}} The young woman was lying in a [[fetal position]], on her right side, and without shoes or socks.<ref name=\"tdn\" /><ref name=namus>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 4790|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/4790|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=7 November 2014|date=10 December 2008}}</ref> These members of the public called police to report their discovery.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Technology Being Used in 'Buckskin Girl' Case|url=https://codingsocieties.com/new-technology-being-used-in-buckskin-girl-case-troy-daily-news/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Autopsy===\nThe decedent's body was autopsied on the afternoon of her discovery. The medical examination revealed she had suffered extensive [[Blunt trauma|blunt force trauma]] to the head and neck,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mullen|first1=Shannon|title=Was Strangled 'Buckskin Girl' from New Jersey?|url=https://eu.app.com/story/news/crime/jersey-mayhem/cold-cases/2016/04/29/buckskin-girl-murder-pollen-nj/83707116/|accessdate=March 31, 2020|date=April 30, 2016}}</ref> before she had been strangled to death<ref name=still/> approximately forty-eight hours before her body was discovered.<ref>{{cite web|title=Buckskin Girl|url=https://dnadoeproject.org/case/buckskin-girl/|website=dnadoeproject.org|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> In addition, her liver had also been lacerated.<ref name=ramsey>{{cite news|last1=Ramsey|first1=Rachelle|title=Jane Doe Doesn't Have a Name or Suspect|url=http://www.officialcoldcaseinvestigations.com/attachment.php?attachmentid=1999&stc=1&d=1348637351|accessdate=September 29, 2015|date=August 29, 1994}}</ref><ref name=jim>{{cite news|last1=DeBrosse|first1=Jim|title='Somebody Cares About Them. We Do':Jane Doe Cases Could be Solved 'Overnight' if Database Utilized, Police Say|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/media/news155.html|accessdate=June 1, 2014|newspaper=Dayton Daily News|date=August 6, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe woman had been between {{cvt|5|ft|4|in|cm}} and {{cvt|5|ft|6|in|cm}} in height, aged between eighteen and twenty-six, and weighed {{convert|125|-|130|lb}}.<ref name=cause/><ref name=id/> She had naturally reddish-brown hair, which was braided into pigtails on both sides of her head.<ref name=doe/><ref name=help/><ref name=id/><ref name=cause>{{cite news|title=Strangulation Cause of Death|url=http://www.officialcoldcaseinvestigations.com/attachment.php?attachmentid=1897&stc=1&d=1332267864|accessdate=September 29, 2015|date=April 27, 1981}}</ref> Her eyes were light brown in color, and she had freckles across her face.<ref name=doe/> In addition, her nose was described as being \"very pointed\".<ref name=watch/> The victim also had a ruddy complexion, indicating she had spent a lot of time outdoors in the final weeks or months of her life.<ref name=doe /><ref name=tri/>\n\nThe young woman had maintained a high level of personal hygiene. All her teeth, including her [[Wisdom tooth|wisdom teeth]], were in good condition and had no evidence of [[Dental restoration|fillings]] or other dental work, except for one porcelain [[Crown (dentistry)|crown]] upon her upper-right [[incisor]].<ref name=namus/><ref name=BGNCMEC/> The coroner also noted several scars upon her body, including a vertical scar under the chin, with other scars visible upon one wrist, both arms and one ankle.<ref name=oh/><ref name=miami>{{cite web |title=Miami Ohio Jane Doe April 1981 |url=http://canyouidentifyme.org/MiamiCountyJaneDoeApril1981 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210190938/http://canyouidentifyme.org/MiamiCountyJaneDoeApril1981 |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 10, 2013 |accessdate=April 13, 2014 |year=2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Clothing===\nThe young woman was dressed in blue bell-bottom [[Wrangler (jeans)|Wrangler]] jeans, a brown turtleneck pullover sweater with an orange crisscross design on the front, a white size 32D bra,<ref name=doe/> and a hoodless deerskin poncho with purple lining, which appeared to be handmade.<ref name=tri>{{cite web|title=Miami County Jane Doe, OH |url=http://meyahna.tripod.com/pg21.html |accessdate=April 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414175922/http://meyahna.tripod.com/pg21.html |archivedate=April 14, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=help>{{cite web|last=Besso |first=Donna |title=Need Help Identifying \"The Buckskin Girl\" |url=http://www.gather.com/viewArticle.action?articleId=281474977406629 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414195811/http://www.gather.com/viewArticle.action?articleId=281474977406629 |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 14, 2014 |accessdate=April 13, 2014 |date=July 25, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=oh>{{cite web|title=Ohio Unsolved Homicides|url=http://www.ohioattorneygeneral.gov/Files/Law-Enforcement/Investigator/Unidentified-Remains|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref> She wore no shoes or socks.<ref name=id>{{cite web|title=Miami Ohio Jane Doe April 1981|url=http://canyouidentifyme.org/MiamiOhioJaneDoeApril1981|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref> No form of identification was located upon her body or at the crime scene.<ref name=oh/><ref name=miami/>\n\n==Initial investigation==\nThe dental charts and fingerprints of this decedent yielded no results matching her to any known missing person, and her fingerprints matched no local police records, indicating she had no criminal record.<ref>{{cite news|title=Buckskin Girl Press Release|url=https://dnadoeproject.org/press-release-for-buckskin-girl/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=pril 11, 2018}}</ref> Early police efforts to identify this decedent also involved the creation of a sketch of the face that was published in local newspapers and broadcast on television networks on April 28, 1981.<ref name=no>{{cite news|title=No identification Yet|url=http://www.officialcoldcaseinvestigations.com/attachment.php?attachmentid=1898&stc=1&d=1332267912|accessdate=September 29, 2015|date=April 28, 1981}}</ref> Initial media publicity surrounding the murder generated approximately two hundred leads. Although all were investigated, all failed to bear fruition.<ref name=still/>\n\nThe victim gradually became known as \"Buckskin Girl\" in reference to the distinctive tasseled buckskin jacket she was wearing when found.<ref name=doe>{{cite web|title=Case File 133UFOH|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/133ufoh.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name=help /><ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Neill|first1=Helen|title=Volunteers Use Computers to Name the Dead|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/tech/news/2008-03-29-naming-dead_N.htm|accessdate=July 23, 2015|work=USA Today|publisher=Associated Press|date=March 30, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAuthorities strongly believed Buckskin Girl had been murdered elsewhere and her body discarded beside the road shortly after her death.<ref name=no/><ref name=cause/> This conclusion was supported by the fact her bare feet were clean, showing no indication of her having walked on dirt, and because [[Interstate 75]] is just {{convert|5|mi|0|spell=in}} from where her body was recovered, making the site a convenient and discreet location to discard a body.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://triblive.com/news/projects/ourstories/10570633-74/doe-jane-hickey|title=Slain Jane Doe's Curious Case in Ohio Still Puzzles After 35 Years|first=Chris|last=Togneri|date=June 4, 2016|website=TribLIVE.com}}</ref> Police and the media later speculated that she may have been a teenage runaway or a possible victim of a serial killer, who murdered multiple sex workers in the region during the 1980s and 1990s.<ref name=jim/><ref name=doe/><ref name=tri/> But the scene and her body showed no signs of sexual assault, rape or other sexual activity, indicating she was unlikely to have been a sex worker.<ref name=doe/> Because of the absence of footwear, some believe she may have been murdered by an abusive significant other.<ref name=watch>{{cite web | url=http://crimewatchdaily.com/2015/10/19/help-crime-watch-daily-and-carl-koppelman-give-names-to-these-5-murder-victims/ | title=Help Crime Watch Daily and Carl Koppelman Give Names to These 5 Murder Victims | publisher=Fox | work=Crime Watch Daily | date=October 10, 2015 | accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> A retired investigator is also known to have opined his belief the decedent was unlikely to be from the area where she was discovered.<ref name=\"whio\" />\n\nThe investigation into Buckskin Girl's murder gradually became a [[cold case]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Winsor|first1=Morgan|title=Jane Doe No More: Miami County Sheriff IDs Cold Case Victim 37 Years Later|url=https://www.whio.com/news/local/miami-county-sheriff-office-release-new-details-1981-unsolved-homicide-case/fmfdENjXMReEHV5VZGPcpI/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|work=[[WHIO-TV]]|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref> although police and other officials continued to investigate her murder. Her clothing and other [[physical evidence]] recovered at the crime scene was retained, and a sample of her blood preserved.<ref name=\"whio\">{{cite news|title=Miami County Authorities Still Working on Jane Doe Case|url=http://www.whio.com/videos/news/miami-county-authorities-still-working-on-jane-doe/vDQhjj/|accessdate=March 29, 2016|work=WHIO|publisher=Cox Media Group|date=April 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425044702/http://www.whio.com/videos/news/miami-county-authorities-still-working-on-jane-doe/vDQhjj/|archive-date=April 25, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Theories==\n===Lifestyle===\nInvestigators theorized that Buckskin Girl had been a runaway teenager, a foster child, or a transient wanderer who had not spent a significant period of time in Ohio prior to her death, although her high quality of personal hygiene strongly indicated that she had not lived as a vagrant.<ref name=doe/> As her body was located close to a town road instead of a highway, the probability of her being a wanderer for a significant amount of time was considered to be negligible.<ref name=watch/> Nonetheless, the failure to establish her identity hindered investigators' efforts to solve her murder. As her identity remained undiscovered, investigating authorities came to increasingly believe the reason Buckskin Girl remained unidentified had been due to the fact that she had been murdered far from her hometown.<ref name=\"perspectives\" />\n\nA 2016 [[isotope analysis]] of the decedent's hair and fingernails revealed Buckskin Girl had spent approximately four months in areas within the [[Southwestern United States|Southwestern]] and/or [[Southeastern United States|Southeastern]] United States, as opposed to Ohio, prior to her murder, although the forensic palynology tests had revealed she had most likely originated from either the Northeastern United States or [[Canada]], or had spent a significant amount of time inn these regions in the year prior to her murder.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 133UFOH|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/133ufoh.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vallieu\">{{cite news|last1=Vallieu|first1=Melody|title='Buckskin Girl' Not From Ohio|url=http://www.tdn-net.com/news/12204/buckskin-girl-not-from-ohio-2|accessdate=January 28, 2018|work=WDTN|agency=Troy Daily News|date=July 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hollenhorst|first1=John|title=Utah Firm Makes Breakthrough in 1981 Ohio Murder Case|url=https://www.ksl.com/?sid=40545046&nid=148&title=utah-firm-makes-breakthrough-in-1981-ohio-murder-case|accessdate=January 28, 2018|work=KSL|date=July 6, 2016}}</ref>\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| header = \n| width     =\n<!-- Image 1 -->\n| image1    = Buckskin Girl.jpg\n| width1    = 120\n| alt1      = \n| caption1  = 2011 [[forensic facial reconstruction]] of Buckskin Girl, depicting her distinctive braided hair.\n<!-- Image 2 -->\n| image2    = Photorealistic reconstruction of Buckskin girl .jpg\n| width2    = 120\n| alt2      = \n| caption2  = Additional facial reconstruction of Buckskin Girl, created prior to her 2018 identification as Marcia Lenore King.\n}}\n\n===Link to other murders===\nInitially, investigators speculated to a potential connection between this decedent and the murder of a 27-year-old woman two months earlier, in February 1981, although police never officially linked these two murders.<ref name=no/>\n\nIn 1985, police temporarily believed that Buckskin Girl had been a victim of a series of murders of sex workers and [[erotic dance]]rs in the area known as the [[Redhead murders|Redhead Murders]]. However, this theory was eventually disproven.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Aldrich|first1=Marta W.|title=Officials Puzzle Over String of Redhead Murders|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1985/Officials-Puzzle-Over-String-of-Redhead-Murders/id-8ad8d3ad5b164d3818827a4768931a2c|accessdate=April 16, 2015|work=Associated Press|date=April 25, 1985|location=Nashville, Tennessee}}</ref>\n\nSome investigators speculate that King was the first of numerous victims killed by an unidentified serial killer who perpetrated his known murders in the 1980s and 1990s, continuing until 2004, in Ohio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.websleuths.com/forums/attachment.php?attachmentid=33483&stc=1&d=1367899621|title=Still No Answers|work=The Blade|year=2004}}</ref> Such a serial killer was suspected to have killed approximately seven to ten other women, presumed sex workers and dancers, in Ohio.<ref name=uns/><ref name=pb91>{{cite news|title=Investigators of 10 Killings to Meet|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19910315&id=goQcAAAAIBAJ&pg=5900,7506894|accessdate=April 16, 2015|work=The Pittsburgh Press|date=March 15, 1991}}</ref> In 1991, a press conference preceded the creation of a task force that attempted to connect various murders in Ohio, New York, Pennsylvania and Illinois.<ref name=pb91/> These cases were originally linked by a reporter who discovered similarities among several unsolved murders in the area.<ref name=uns/>\n\nOn an episode of ''[[Unsolved Mysteries]],'' the Buckskin Girl case was briefly described, along with several other cases connected to the unidentified serial killer.<ref name=doe/> The program connected this case with the murders of Shirley Dee Taylor, Anna Marie Patterson, Hebron Jane Doe (identified in 2017 as [[Patrice Corley]])<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sneed|first1=Rob|title=Licking County Sheriff Identifies Jane Doe in 1990 Homicide Case|url=http://nbc4i.com/2017/08/30/licking-county-sheriff-identifies-jane-doe-in-1990-homicide-victim/|accessdate=September 26, 2017|date=August 30, 2017}}</ref> and other murder cases. All the victims had been beaten or strangled and had some clothing or jewelry missing. King was found without jewelry or footwear, and was killed in a manner similar to that of the other victims.<ref name=uns>{{cite web|title=Prostitute Serial Killer|url=http://unsolved.com/archives/prostitute-serial-killer|website=unsolved.com|publisher=[[Unsolved Mysteries]]|accessdate=April 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSeveral elements of evidence were found to contradict this theory. There was no indication Buckskin Girl had engaged in any form of sexual activity prior to her death.<ref name=doe/><ref name=uns/> In addition, unlike many of the victims of this serial killer, she was markedly well-groomed, with a history of dental care.<ref name=uns/><ref name=pb91/>\n\nIn 1987, police theorized that the women who may have been victims of the serial killer could have met with a man at a truck stop while working as sex workers. In the case of Anna Marie Patterson, there was a suspect, identified over a [[CB radio]] as \"Dr. No\", believed to be between the ages of 25 and 40.<ref name=uns/><ref name=sought/> Patterson's husband, who was involved with her work as a sex worker, said that she was uncomfortable accepting the man's requests. Other local sex workers, some speaking over the radio, had also said that they were suspicious of the man and did not want to take his trade. Police have suspected that this person may have been Patterson's killer, and that he may also have been involved in King's murder.<ref name=sought>{{cite news|title=Mysterious 'Dr. No\" Sought in Ohio Truck Stop Prostitute Murder|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19870419&id=gZMcAAAAIBAJ&pg=6860,829029|accessdate=April 16, 2015|work=The Pittsburgh Press|date=April 19, 1987}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, an Arizona man was linked to a series of rapes and murders in the Ohio area that occurred in the 1990s. Investigators in the Patrice Corley case, however, do not believe he was responsible for her murder.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sumner |first1=Michaela |title=County Prosecutor Doesn't Believe Arizona Man Connected to 1990 Patrice Corley Homicide |url=https://www.newarkadvocate.com/story/news/local/2019/02/18/county-prosecutor-doesnt-believe-arizona-man-tied-1990-homicide/2904061002/ |accessdate=February 20, 2019 |work=The Newark Advocate |date=February 18, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Ongoing investigation==\n===Further forensic analysis===\nBecause the decedent's body was found approximately forty-eight hours after her death,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mullen |first1=Shannon |title=Was Strangled 'Buckskin Girl' from New Jersey? |url=https://eu.app.com/story/news/crime/jersey-mayhem/cold-cases/2016/04/29/buckskin-girl-murder-pollen-nj/83707116 |accessdate=March 27, 2020|publisher=USA Today |date=April 30, 2016}}</ref> police were able to obtain her fingerprints, dental information, and a [[Genetic testing|DNA sample]].<ref name=namus/> With the increasing use of DNA analysis in criminal investigations, the case benefited by her DNA being added to the growing number of law enforcement databases.<ref name=\"whio\" />\n\nIn 2001, the Miami Valley Regional Crime Laboratory generated a [[DNA profiling|DNA profile]] of Buckskin Girl,<ref name=\"sossoman\" /> this data was entered into the newly established [[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]] (NamUs) database in 2008, through which her fingerprints, dental and DNA information were made nationally accessible to law enforcement.<ref name=\"perspectives\">{{cite book|title=New Perspectives in Forensic Human Skeletal Identification|editor1=Krista E. Latham|editor2=Eric J. Bartelink|editor3=Michael Finnegan|date=July 28, 2017|publisher=Elsevier, Inc.|isbn=978-0-12-805429-1|pages=124\u2013125|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jhdHDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA124&lpg=PA124&sig=AUEKTXjtDwA-hpSQptDTfynNu68&ved=0ahUKEwj_k5zNw6bXAhVMwWMKHXCwBxwQ6AEIQjAF#v=onepage&q=NamUS%3A%204790|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref> This data was able to concludsively rule out any possibility of 226 missing teenage girls and young women as Buckskin Girl.<ref name=namus/> In 2009, a [[mitochondrial DNA]] sample was submitted to the [[FBI]] for inclusion within the [[Combined DNA Index System]] (CODIS).<ref>{{cite news|title=Buckskin Girl Press Release|url=https://dnadoeproject.org/press-release-for-buckskin-girl/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=pril 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe following year, NamUs case management was assigned to Dr Elizabeth Murray, a [[Cincinnati]] based [[Forensic anthropology|forensic anthropologist]] and professor of biology, who remained involved with the case.<ref name=\"sossoman\" />\n[[File:Buckskin Girl NCMEC.jpg|150px|thumb|upright|[[Forensic facial reconstruction]] of Buckskin Girl, created by the [[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]]]\n\n===Facial reconstruction===\nIn April 2016, the [[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]] released an updated [[forensic facial reconstruction]] of the victim and added her case to their website, depicting her with and without her braided pigtails.<ref name=\"BGNCMEC\">{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1981|url=http://missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1107106/|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]]|accessdate=February 12, 2016|date=February 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Pollen analysis===\nIn 2016, the Miami County Police Department approved [[forensic palynology]] testing upon the victim's clothing in their efforts to identify her and her murderer(s). This testing was conducted by the [[United States Border Patrol|U.S. Customs and Border Protection Agency]].<ref name=\"vallieu\"/> The results of this testing suggested Buckskin Girl had either originated within the [[Northeastern United States|Northeastern]] United States, or had spent a significant amount of time in this region in the year prior to her murder. Her clothing also contained high levels of soot from exposure to vehicular traffic and/or industrial activity, supporting investigators' initial suspicions she may have been a habitual hitchhiker.<ref name=\"kennedy\">{{cite news|last1=Kennedy|first1=Megan|title=Miami Co. Cold Case Heats Up With Facial Reconstruction, Other developments|url=http://wdtn.com/2016/04/27/miami-co-cold-case-heats-up-with-facial-reconstruction-other-developments/|accessdate=April 28, 2016|work=WDTN News|agency=LIN Television Corporation|publisher=Media General|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref> In addition, the pollen<ref>{{cite news|last1=Norman|first1=Greg|title='Buckskin Girl' Identified After Being Found Dead in Ohio 37 Years Ago|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/buckskin-girl-identified-after-being-found-dead-in-ohio-37-years-ago|accessdate=April 2, 2020|work=Fox News|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> recovered from her external clothing suggested that, shortly before her murder, she had been in an arid climate such as the [[Western United States|Western]] United States, or northern [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Baker|first=Steve|title=New Developments Could ID 'Jane Doe' Found Dead 35 Years Ago|url=http://www.whio.com/videos/news/new-developments-could-id-jane-doe-found-dead-35/vDqjK2/|accessdate=April 28, 2016|work=WHIO|publisher=Cox Media Group|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Identification==\nOn April 9, 2018, the Miami Valley Crime Laboratory announced they had identified the decedent as 21-year-old Marcia Lenore King of [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]], [[Arkansas]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=\"Buckskin Girl\" Case: DNA Breakthrough Leads to ID of 1981 Murder Victim|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/buckskin-girl-case-groundbreaking-dna-tech-leads-to-id-of-1981-murder-victim/|accessdate=April 13, 2018|work=Crimesider|agency=American Broadcasting Company|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> Her identification had been achieved via [[Genetic testing|DNA analysis]] conducted by the [[DNA Doe Project]], with assistance from the Miami Valley Regional Crime Laboratory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forensicmag.com/news/2018/04/buck-skin-girl-case-break-success-new-dna-doe-project|title='Buck Skin Girl' Case Break is Success of New DNA Doe Project|date=April 16, 2018|publisher=Forensic Magazine|author=Seth Augenstein}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/611048/the-brave-new-world-of-genetic-genealogy/|title=The Brave New World of Genetic Genealogy|first=Debbie|last=Kennett|work=MIT Technology Review|date=April 28, 2018}}</ref> This organization was able to successfully match King's DNA to a sample submitted for comparison by a first cousin.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/04/golden-state-killer-east-area-rapist-dna-genealogy/559070/|title=How a Genealogy Website Led to the Alleged Golden State Killer|first=Sarah|last=Zhang|date=April 27, 2018|accessdate=March 29, 2020|work=[[The Atlantic]]}}</ref>\n\nKing had last been seen by her family in 1980. She had never officially been reported as a [[missing person]], although her family had continued to search for her.<ref name=\"tdn\">{{cite news|last1=Vallieu|first1=Melody|title='Buckskin Girl' Identified|url=http://www.tdn-net.com/top-stories/39213/buckskin-girl-identified|accessdate=April 12, 2018|work=Troy Daily News|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref> It is believed King had hitchhiked as the primary means of transportation, as investigators had theorized prior to her identification. She is also known to have had ties with both the [[Pittsburg, Kentucky|Pittsburg]] and [[Louisville, Kentucky]] districts.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jane 'Buckskin Girl' Doe Identified After 37 Years|url=https://www.fox19.com/story/37935396/jane-buckskin-girl-doe-identified-after-37-years/|work=[[Fox 19]]|accessdate=March 28, 2020|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|In the hope her daughter would initiate contact, King's mother had both continued to reside at the same house she lived in at the time of her daughter's disappearance, and kept the same phone number, should her daughter either return home or telephone her.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Dana|title=Cold Case Homicide Victim Identified after 37 Years|url=http://www.wdtn.com/news/local-news/cold-case-homicide-victim-identified-after-37-years/1116096993|work=WTDN 2|accessdate=April 13, 2018|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nAddressing the media to announce the formal identification of Buckskin Girl, a spokesman for the Miami County Police Department informed all present: \"Law enforcement never forgets. We've had a long journey to [be] where we are today.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eustachewich|first1=Lia|title=Murdered 'Buckskin Girl' Finally Identified 37 Years Later |url=https://nypost.com/2018/04/12/murdered-buckskin-girl-finally-identified-37-years-later/|work=The New York Post|accessdate=April 1, 2020|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> This spokesman also emphasized the investigation into King's homicide is ongoing.<ref name=\"miamiID\"/>\n\n===Ongoing investigation===\nIn July 2018, the Miami County Police Department announced they had received further information regarding King's actual whereabouts shortly prior to her death. This information included eyewitness accounts placing her in Louisville, Kentucky, approximately 14 days before her death.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.whio.com/news/local/buckskin-girl-grave-troy-get-new-headstone-with-her-name/nNQOsP1P8P4v40J6byXJvN/|title=Gravesite for 'Buckskin Girl': Gets New Headstone With Her Name|date=July 20, 2018|author=Nancy Bowman|work=whiotv}}</ref> Six eyewitnesses have also [[Corroborating evidence|corroborated]] accounts of King also being in Arkansas shortly before her murder. It is belieleived the reason she had traveled to Ohio may have been due to her suspected involvement with a religious organization.<ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite news |last1=Thomason |first1=Tyler |title=Ohio Cold Case Develops New Timeline, Puts Murder Victim in Arkansas Two Weeks Before Death |url=https://www.fox16.com/news/top-stories/ohio-cold-case-develops-new-timeline-puts-murder-victim-in-arkansas-two-weeks-before-death/1915607781 |accessdate=June 9, 2019 |work=FOX16 |date=April 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, the Miami County Sheriff's Office announced they had been able to further reconstruct King's whereabouts, and relationships, in the two weeks prior to her murder,<ref>{{cite news|title=Forensic Genealogy to Be Used in Miami County Unsolved Homicides|url=https://www.whio.com/news/local/forensic-genealogy-used-miami-county-unsolved-homicides/oAl1az1NfGHbopAT29pW3M/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|work=WHIO|date=February 13, 2020}}</ref> adding that as advances in technology now mean [[Nuclear DNA]] samples can be retrieved from hair samples missing the actual [[hair#Root of the hair|root]], they remained confident hair samples discovered at the crime scene and submitted to a renowned Californian [[Paleogenetics|paleogeneticist]] could yield a Nuclear DNA profile of either her murderer, ar an individual she had been in the company of very shortly before her death.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Technology Being Used in 'Buckskin Girl' Case|url=https://codingsocieties.com/new-technology-being-used-in-buckskin-girl-case-troy-daily-news/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=February 22, 2020}}</ref> Addressing these latest developments, Miami County Sheriff Dave Duchalk stated: \"We always have hopes to bring justice for homicide victims and their families. We never have, nor will we ever forget, and will continually work the case and, as new technologies are developed, will review our evidence to learn if it is worth re-submitting.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=New Technology Being Used in 'Buckskin Girl' Case|url=https://www.tdn-net.com/news/79673/new-technology-being-used-in-buckskin-girl-case|accessdate=March 26, 2020|date=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n{{quote box\n| quote = \"They were hopeful Marcia was going to come home. However, they are learning at this date that that's not going to happen.\"\n| source = [[Miami County, Ohio|Miami County]] Sheriff Steve Lord, addressing the media to announce the formal identification of Buckskin Girl. April 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=After 37 Years, Murder Victim Buckskin Girl Has Her Name Back|url=https://torontosun.com/news/world/crime-hunter-after-37-years-murder-victim-buckskin-girl-has-her-name-back|accessdate=March 26, 2020|date=April 14, 2018}}</ref>\n| width = 30em\n}}\n\n==Funeral==\nKing had been buried as a Jane Doe at Riverside Cemetery in Miami County weeks after her death, with several officers assigned to investigate her murder serving as [[pallbearer]]s at her funeral.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mullen |first1=Shannon |title=Was Strangled 'Buckskin Girl' from New Jersey? |url=https://eu.app.com/story/news/crime/jersey-mayhem/cold-cases/2016/04/29/buckskin-girl-murder-pollen-nj/83707116 |accessdate=March 27, 2020|publisher=USA Today |date=April 30, 2016}}</ref> Following the identification of her body, King's family chose for her to remain buried within this cemetery, with her stepmother, Cindy Sossoman, explaining her family's belief that, had it been God's plan that their daughter was to be murdered and to remain unidentified for so long, they believed King was [[Blessing|blessed]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ullery |first1=Michael |title=Sossoman Given Back Her Name |url=https://www.tdn-net.com/news/44910/sossoman-given-back-her-name |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Troy Daily News |publisher=AIM Media Midwest |date=July 20, 2018}}</ref> to have passed away within a community which had shown such consideration and dignity to her while she had remained unidentified.<ref name=sossoman/> Her parents had long since divorced, and her father, John Wesley Sossoman, had remarried, having several children with his second wife, all of whom had long wondered as to King's wherebouts and welfare.<ref name=sossoman/>\n\nOn July 20, 2018, a memorial service for King was held at a local chapel. This service was officiated by the Reverend Gregory Simmons. Her new headstone was unveiled at this service.<ref name=sossoman>{{cite news |last1=Ullery |first1=Michael |title=Sossoman Given Back Her Name |url=https://www.tdn-net.com/news/44910/sossoman-given-back-her-name |accessdate=July 24, 2018 |work=Troy Daily News |publisher=AIM Media Midwest |date=July 20, 2018}}</ref> Marcia's father, John, had died on January 5, 2018. Her brother, Daniel King, and half-brother, Jonathan Sossoman, had also died by the time of King's identity being discovered.<ref name=\"penwell\" /> Her stepmother and eight other surviving family members replaced the headstone simply reading \"Jane Doe\" with a headstone bearing her actual name at this service, which was attended by over fifty local residents. Describing King's personality, her stepmother described her as a \"very trusting\" young woman, before informing all present: \"Words don't describe the feelings we have for all of you, how you have loved her and taken her in your arms.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bowman |first1=Nancy |title=Gravesite for 'Buckskin Girl' Gets New Headstone with Her Name |url=https://www.springfieldnewssun.com/news/local/buckskin-girl-grave-troy-get-new-headstone-with-her-name/nNQOsP1P8P4v40J6byXJvN/ |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |publisher=Springfield News-Sun |date=July 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Cold case]]\n* [[Crime in Ohio]]\n* [[List of formerly unidentified decedents]]\n{{col-break}}\n* [[The Doe Network]]\n* [[Unidentified decedent]]\n* [[List of solved missing persons cases]]\n* [[List of unsolved deaths|Unsolved murders]]\n{{col-end}}\n{{Portal bar|1980s|Law|Ohio}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Cited works and further reading==\n* {{cite book| last = Halber| first = Deborah| title = The Skeleton Crew: How Amateur Sleuths Are Solving America's Coldest Cases| year = 2015| publisher = Simon & Schuster | location = New York| isbn = 978-1-451-65758-6}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Katz|first=H\u00e9l\u00e8na|title=Cold Cases: Famous Unsolved Mysteries, Crimes, and Disappearances in America|year=2010|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|location=Santa Barbara|isbn=978-0-313-37692-4}}\n* {{cite book| last = Murray| first = Elizabeth A.| title = Forensic Identification: Putting a Name and Face on Death| year = 2012| publisher = Twenty-First Century Books | location = Minneapolis| isbn = 978-1-467-70139-6}}\n* {{cite book| last = Newton| first = Michael| title = The Encyclopedia of Unsolved Crimes| year = 2004| publisher = Facts on File | location = New York| isbn = 978-0-816-07818-9}}\n* {{cite book| last = Pettem| first = Silvia| title = The Long Term Missing: Hope and Help for Families| year = 2017| publisher = Rowman & Littlefield | location = Maryland| isbn = 978-1-442-25680-4}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Shoester|first=Maria|title=Forensics in Law Enforcement|year=2006|publisher=[[Nova Science Publishers, Inc.]]|location=New York|isbn=978-1-600-21164-5}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Marcia King}}\n* [https://www.whio.com/news/crime--law/with-buckskin-girl-investigation-intensifies-into-unsolved-homicide/Fz5capsVOPZknmNAxuYDCP/ Contemporary news article] pertaining to the 2018 forensic identification of Buckskin Girl\n* [[DNA Doe Project]] [https://dnadoeproject.org/case/buckskin-girl/ ''webpage''] pertaining to the identification of Buckskin Girl\n* {{Find a Grave|124674061|Marcia King}}\n\n{{Unidentified decedent}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King, Marcia}}\n[[Category:1980s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:1981 in Ohio]]\n[[Category:1981 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by beating in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by strangulation in the United States]]\n[[Category:Female murder victims]]\n[[Category:Forensic palynology]]\n[[Category:Incidents of violence against women]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Unsolved murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFuneral:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: wherebouts \u2192 whereabouts", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murder_of_Marcia_King"}
{"title_page": "Volumnia Cytheris", "text_new": "{{short description|Ancient Roman actress and dancer}}\n{{more footnotes|date=December 2019}}\n\n'''Volumnia Cytheris''' (fl. 1st-century BC) was an Ancient Roman actress and mimae dancer. She is foremost known as the mistress of several famous Romans. \n\nShe was originally a slave and later [[Freedman|freedwoman]]. Onstage, she was normally referred to only as Cytheris.  She had relationships with [[Marcus Junius Brutus the Younger|Brutus]] and [[Mark Antony]], which attracted a lot of attention in contemporary Ancient Rome.  She is mentioned as the companion of her aristocratic lovers in social occasions when the presence of a courtesan was otherwise not common, and considered shocking. \n\nHer rejection of [[Cornelius Gallus]] reportedly provided the theme for [[Virgil]]'s tenth [[Eclogues|Eclogue]].<ref>Sarah B. Pomeroy, ''Goddesses, Whores, Wives, and Slaves'', pp 198\u20139 {{ISBN|0-8052-1030-X}}</ref>  Gallus refers to her in his work under the name ''Lycoris''.\n\nShe is one of few free influential Roman courtesans mentioned by her contemporaries, others being [[Praecia]] and [[Chelidon]].<ref> Anise K. Strong: ''[https://books.google.se/books?id=ClSJDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA47&lpg=PA47&dq=Hispala+Faecenia&source=bl&ots=s1z6EfUJy5&sig=ACfU3U2EzwHP6MvJQAjygcYpODQB8YwWKA&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjTrY_gzaLnAhXPvosKHb0yDW0Q6AEwD3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Hispala%20Faecenia&f=false     Prostitutes and Matrons in the Roman World]'' </ref>\n==See also==\n* [[ Tertia (actress)]]\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Matthew Dillon, Lynda Garland, ''[https://books.google.se/books?id=Ce3WAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA382&lpg=PA382&dq=Eucharis+actress+ancient+rome&source=bl&ots=bUk3WOZdg2&sig=ACfU3U028LZWCHcbRRzpiMe5RFXG_TMGEw&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjwoLiopablAhWM16YKHbHtCy8Q6AEwF3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Eucharis%20actress%20ancient%20rome&f=false  Ancient Rome: A Sourcebook]''\n* Edith Hall, Rosie Wyles, ''[https://books.google.se/books?id=9N0GmN1wiLsC&pg=PA186&dq=Eucharis+actress+ancient+rome+mimae&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjtx6vnq6blAhVH0aYKHWprAJoQ6AEIOzAC#v=onepage&q=Eucharis%20actress%20ancient%20rome%20mimae&f=false  New Directions in Ancient Pantomime]''\n\n{{AncientRome-bio-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Ancient actresses]]\n[[Category:Roman courtesans]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC Roman women]]\n[[Category:Ancient Roman theatre practitioners]]\n[[Category:Mistresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ancient Roman actress and dancer}}\n{{more footnotes|date=December 2019}}\n\n'''Volumnia Cytheris''' (fl. 1st-century BC) was a Ancient Roman actress and mimae dancer. She is foremost known as the mistress of several famous Romans. \n\nShe was originally a slave and later [[Freedman|freedwoman]]. Onstage, she was normally referred to only as Cytheris.  She had relationships with [[Marcus Junius Brutus the Younger|Brutus]] and [[Mark Antony]], which attracted a lot of attention in contemporary Ancient Rome.  She is mentioned as the companion of her aristocratic lovers in social occasions when the presence of a courtesan was otherwise not common, and considered shocking. \n\nHer rejection of [[Cornelius Gallus]] reportedly provided the theme for [[Virgil]]'s tenth [[Eclogues|Eclogue]].<ref>Sarah B. Pomeroy, ''Goddesses, Whores, Wives, and Slaves'', pp 198\u20139 {{ISBN|0-8052-1030-X}}</ref>  Gallus refers to her in his work under the name ''Lycoris''.\n\nShe is one of few free influential Roman courtesans mentioned by her contemporaries, others being [[Praecia]] and [[Chelidon]].<ref> Anise K. Strong: ''[https://books.google.se/books?id=ClSJDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA47&lpg=PA47&dq=Hispala+Faecenia&source=bl&ots=s1z6EfUJy5&sig=ACfU3U2EzwHP6MvJQAjygcYpODQB8YwWKA&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjTrY_gzaLnAhXPvosKHb0yDW0Q6AEwD3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Hispala%20Faecenia&f=false     Prostitutes and Matrons in the Roman World]'' </ref>\n==See also==\n* [[ Tertia (actress)]]\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Matthew Dillon, Lynda Garland, ''[https://books.google.se/books?id=Ce3WAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA382&lpg=PA382&dq=Eucharis+actress+ancient+rome&source=bl&ots=bUk3WOZdg2&sig=ACfU3U028LZWCHcbRRzpiMe5RFXG_TMGEw&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjwoLiopablAhWM16YKHbHtCy8Q6AEwF3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Eucharis%20actress%20ancient%20rome&f=false  Ancient Rome: A Sourcebook]''\n* Edith Hall, Rosie Wyles, ''[https://books.google.se/books?id=9N0GmN1wiLsC&pg=PA186&dq=Eucharis+actress+ancient+rome+mimae&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjtx6vnq6blAhVH0aYKHWprAJoQ6AEIOzAC#v=onepage&q=Eucharis%20actress%20ancient%20rome%20mimae&f=false  New Directions in Ancient Pantomime]''\n\n{{AncientRome-bio-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Ancient actresses]]\n[[Category:Roman courtesans]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC Roman women]]\n[[Category:Ancient Roman theatre practitioners]]\n[[Category:Mistresses]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: a Ancient \u2192 an Ancient", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volumnia_Cytheris"}
{"title_page": "Chelidon", "text_new": "'''Chelidon''' (fl. 74 BC) was a Roman courtesan, famed for her influence during the praetorship of [[Gaius Verres]]. <ref> Anise K. Strong: ''[https://books.google.se/books?id=ClSJDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA47&lpg=PA47&dq=Hispala+Faecenia&source=bl&ots=s1z6EfUJy5&sig=ACfU3U2EzwHP6MvJQAjygcYpODQB8YwWKA&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjTrY_gzaLnAhXPvosKHb0yDW0Q6AEwD3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Hispala%20Faecenia&f=false     Prostitutes and Matrons in the Roman World]'' </ref>  \n\nShe was a freedwoman and a successful professional high class courtesan. She was introduced to [[Gaius Verres]] by the courtesan Pippa and [[Tertia (actress)]], and became his mistress.<ref>Anise K. Strong: ''[https://books.google.se/books?id=ClSJDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA79&lpg=PA79&dq=Verres+tertia+chelidon&source=bl&ots=s1z7KbPCzb&sig=ACfU3U1SklMXhjIjCTm4rM_WhjTSPo__kQ&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj5_OqD7M_nAhVHl4sKHR3PAJkQ6AEwAHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=Verres%20tertia%20chelidon&f=false Prostitutes and Matrons in the Roman World]''</ref> \n\nShe became known for the influence the vielded ower public affairs in 74 BC, when her lover Gaius Verres served as urban praetor of Rome.  Her influence was used against Gaius Verres by his enemies, who accused him of allowing her an eccessive influence over state affairs.  Allegedly, she acted as the political advisor of Gaius Verres, who allowed her to make decisions within civil cases and prepare laws and political reforms.  Aware of her de facto position, she was courted by supplicants and political officials. \n\nShe died between 73 and 71 BC, when Verres apparently received an inheritance from her. \n\nShe is one of few free influential Roman courtesans mentioned by her contemporaries, others being [[Volumnia Cytheris]] and [[Praecia]].<ref> Anise K. Strong: ''[https://books.google.se/books?id=ClSJDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA47&lpg=PA47&dq=Hispala+Faecenia&source=bl&ots=s1z6EfUJy5&sig=ACfU3U2EzwHP6MvJQAjygcYpODQB8YwWKA&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjTrY_gzaLnAhXPvosKHb0yDW0Q6AEwD3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Hispala%20Faecenia&f=false     Prostitutes and Matrons in the Roman World]'' </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Expand Swedish| Chelidon |date=January 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:}}\n\n[[Category:1st-century BC Roman women]]\n[[Category:Roman courtesans]]\n", "text_old": "'''Chelidon''' (fl. 74 BC) was a Roman courtesan, famed for her influence during the praetorship of [[Gaius Verres]]. <ref> Anise K. Strong: ''[https://books.google.se/books?id=ClSJDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA47&lpg=PA47&dq=Hispala+Faecenia&source=bl&ots=s1z6EfUJy5&sig=ACfU3U2EzwHP6MvJQAjygcYpODQB8YwWKA&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjTrY_gzaLnAhXPvosKHb0yDW0Q6AEwD3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Hispala%20Faecenia&f=false     Prostitutes and Matrons in the Roman World]'' </ref>  \n\nShe was a freedwoman and a succesfull professional high class courtesan. She was introduced to [[Gaius Verres]] by the courtesan Pippa and [[Tertia (actress)]], and became his mistress.<ref>Anise K. Strong: ''[https://books.google.se/books?id=ClSJDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA79&lpg=PA79&dq=Verres+tertia+chelidon&source=bl&ots=s1z7KbPCzb&sig=ACfU3U1SklMXhjIjCTm4rM_WhjTSPo__kQ&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj5_OqD7M_nAhVHl4sKHR3PAJkQ6AEwAHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=Verres%20tertia%20chelidon&f=false Prostitutes and Matrons in the Roman World]''</ref> \n\nShe became known for the influence the vielded ower public affairs in 74 BC, when her lover Gaius Verres served as urban praetor of Rome.  Her influence was used against Gaius Verres by his enemies, who accused him of allowing her an eccessive influence over state affairs.  Alledgedly, she acted as the political advisor of Gaius Verres, who allowed her to make decisions within civil cases and prepare laws and political reforms.  Aware of her de facto position, she was courted by supplicants and political officials. \n\nShe died between 73 and 71 BC, when Verres apparently received an inheritance from her. \n\nShe is one of few free influential Roman courtesans mentioned by her contemporaries, others being [[Volumnia Cytheris]] and [[Praecia]].<ref> Anise K. Strong: ''[https://books.google.se/books?id=ClSJDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA47&lpg=PA47&dq=Hispala+Faecenia&source=bl&ots=s1z6EfUJy5&sig=ACfU3U2EzwHP6MvJQAjygcYpODQB8YwWKA&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjTrY_gzaLnAhXPvosKHb0yDW0Q6AEwD3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Hispala%20Faecenia&f=false     Prostitutes and Matrons in the Roman World]'' </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Expand Swedish| Chelidon |date=January 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:}}\n\n[[Category:1st-century BC Roman women]]\n[[Category:Roman courtesans]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: succesfull \u2192 successfull, Alledgedly \u2192 Allegedly, full \u2192 ful", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chelidon"}
{"title_page": "Els von Eystett", "text_new": "'''Els von Eystett''' (also Els von Eichst\u00e4tt) was woman who worked in a public [[brothel]] in [[N\u00f6rdlingen]], Germany, in the late fifteenth century. Els originally worked in the brothel as a kitchen maid and later as a prostitute. Her experiences are documented in the records of a criminal investigation carried out by the city council of N\u00f6rdlingen between December 1471 and January 1472. \n\nThe investigation was first prompted by rumours that Els had become pregnant by a customer, and had subsequently been forced by the brothel madam to terminate her pregnancy by means of a herbal [[abortifacient]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Schuster |first1=Peter |title=Das Frauenhaus. St\u00e4dtische Bordelle in Deutschland 1350-1600 |date=1992 |publisher=F. Sch\u00f6ningh |page=92|isbn=9783506782519}}</ref> The inquiry later expanded to involve the interrogation of all twelve women working in N\u00f6rdlingen's brothel in the latter half of 1471, as well as the brothel madam Barbara Tarscheinfeindin and brothel-keeper Lienhart Fryermut. As several of the women in the brothel had left N\u00f6rdlingen by the time the interrogations began (including Els herself) the investigation also involved cooperation between the authorities in N\u00f6rdlingen and the city councils of [[Nuremberg]] and [[Wei\u00dfenburg in Bayern]]. \n\nOriginal transcriptions of the women's testimony are held today in [https://www.noerdlingen.de/verwaltung/einrichtungen/archiv/ N\u00f6rdlingen's civic archive]. The case record offers the most comprehensive vision of prostitution currently known to have survived from medieval Europe which shows the perspectives of prostitutes themselves.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=69 |issue=6 |pages=28-39 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref> Els's story has been the subject of several magazine articles,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=69 |issue=6 |pages=28-39 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref> <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Thadeusz |first1=Frank |title=Paar des Grauens |journal=Der Spiegel |date=15 June 2019|volume=2019 |issue=25 |url=https://magazin.spiegel.de/SP/2019/25/164407550/}}</ref> a TV documentary,<ref>{{cite web |title=K\u00e4ufliche Liebe im Mittelalter. Wie Wanderhuren wirklich lebten |url=https://bilderfest.de/index.php?article_id=51&clang=0 |website=Bilderfest GmbH}}</ref> and a theatrical production,<ref>{{cite web |title=Els - Die Frauenhausakte von N\u00f6rdlingen |url=http://www.freilichtbuehne-noerdlingen.de/index.php |website=Freilichtb\u00fchne N\u00f6rdlingen}}</ref> and has been the focus of modern research into prostitution in medieval Europe. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Schuster |first1=Peter |editor1-last=H\u00f6dl |editor1-first=G\u00fcnther |editor2-last=Mayrhofer |editor2-first=Fritz |editor3-last=Opll |editor3-first=Ferdinand |title=Stadt der Frauen |date=2003 |location=Linz |pages=265-91 |language=German |chapter=Lebensbedingungen der Prostituierten in der sp\u00e4tmittelalterlichen Stadt}}</ref> <ref>{{cite book |last1=Schuster |first1=Peter |title=Das Frauenhaus. St\u00e4dtische Bordelle in Deutschland 1350-1600 |publisher=F. Sch\u00f6ningh |location=Paderborn |pages=11, 92, 113}}</ref> <ref>{{cite journal |last1=R\u00e4uschel |first1=Lara-Sophie |title=Das N\u00f6rdlinger Frauenhaus und die Justiz. Der Abtreibungsfall der Dirne Els von Eystett (Reichsstadt N\u00f6rdlingen, Reichsstadt Wei\u00dfenburg) |journal=Historischer Verein f\u00fcr N\u00f6rdlingen und das Ries Jahrbuch |date=2014 |issue=35 |pages=1-35}}</ref>\n\n===Prostitution in medieval Europe===\n\nPublic brothels of the kind that Els von Eystett worked in were a common feature in towns across much of western Europe in the period ca. 1350\u20131550.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mazo Karras |first1=Ruth |editor1-last=Brundage |editor1-first=James A. |editor2-last=Bullough |editor2-first=Vern L. |title=Handbook of Medieval Sexuality |date=2000 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |location=New York |pages=244-5 |chapter=Prostitution in Medieval Europe}}</ref> Although the medieval Church condemned prostitution and saw prostitutes themselves as sinful women,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Brundage |first1=James A. |title=Prostitution in the Medieval Canon Law |journal=Signs |date=1976 |volume=1 |issue=4 |page=830}}</ref> it was generally accepted that tolerating prostitution in society represented a lesser evil than banning it altogether.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mazo Karras |first1=Ruth |editor1-last=Brundage |editor1-first=James A. |editor2-last=Bullough |editor2-first=Vern L. |title=Handbook of Medieval Sexuality |publisher=Taylor & Francis |location=New York |page=245 |chapter=Prostitution in Medieval Europe}}</ref> This position was upheld by a number of major ecclesiastical figures including [[St. Augustine]] <ref>{{cite book |last1=Augustine |editor1-last=Green |editor1-first=W. M. |title=Sancti Aurelii Augustini: Contra academicos; De beata vita; De ordine (Corpus Christianorum Series Latina 29) |date=1970 |location=Turnhout |page=114}}</ref> and [[St. Thomas Aquinas]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dever |first1=Vincent |title=Aquinas and the Practice of Prostitution |journal=Essays in Medieval Studies |date=1996 |volume=13 |pages=39-49}}</ref>\n\nIn southern and central Germany, where public brothels were much more common than in the north,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hemmie |first1=Dagmar M. H. |title=Ungeordnete Unzucht. Prostitution im Hanseraum (12.-16. Jahrhundert). L\u00fcbeck - Bergen - Helsing\u00f8r |date=2007 |publisher=B\u00f6hlau |location=Cologne |page=126}}</ref> brothels typically operated on a leaseholder model which saw a brothel-keeper (''Frauenwirt/in'') pay civic authorities for the right to run the brothel. Rules governing the relationship between brothel-keepers and the authorities were set out in lease agreements, and frequently in oaths sworn by brothel-keepers which required them to make promises of loyalty and obedience. These documents frequently also contained 'house rules' specifying the behaviour forbidden in brothels (such as drunkenness and blasphemy) and governing the relations between prostitutes and the brothel-keeper.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Isenmann |first1=Eberhard |title=Die Deutsche Stadt im Mittelalter, 1150-1550 |date=2012 |publisher=B\u00f6hlau |location=Vienna |page=475}}</ref> \n\nProstitutes themselves typically lived in the brothel, and as well as paying for board and lodging were required to give the brothel-keeper a certain amount of the money they received from clients. This usually amounted to one third of their earnings.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Peter |first1=Schuster |title=Das Frauenhaus. St\u00e4dtische Bordelle in Deutschland 1350-1600 |date=1992 |publisher=F. Sch\u00f6ningh |location=Paderborn |page=113}}</ref> Most cities permitted brothel-keepers to contract debts with prostitutes or to accept women as pawns, requiring them to pay off debts through their labour. Partly as a consequence of this, prostitutes were often heavily in debt to brothel-keepers, and many were traded between brothels.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schuster |first1=Beate |title=Frauenhandel und Frauenh\u00e4user im 15. und im 16. Jahrhundert |journal=VSWG: Vierteljahrschrift f\u00fcr Sozial- und Wirtschaftsgeschichte |date=1991 |volume=2 |issue=78}}</ref> \n\n===The N\u00f6rdlingen investigations of 1471-2===\n\nThe transcriptions produced from the testimony of Els von Eystett and the other women of N\u00f6rdlingen's brothel form the primary source of information about the investigation. Sentencing records for Barbara Tarschenfeindin and Lienhart Fryermut are also held in N\u00f6rdlingen's civic archive in the city's so-called blood book (''Blutbuch''), a medieval and early modern record of criminal punishments, and the town's collection of ''[https://www.historisches-lexikon-bayerns.de/Lexikon/Urfehden Urfehden]'', a form of judicial oath.\n\nThe women's statements indicate that the investigation proceeded along two lines: a specific inquiry into the rumours of Els's abortion, and a more general inquiry into the working conditions in the brothel, ostensibly prompted by Els's claims of other abuses by Barbara and Lienhart.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=6 |issue=69 |page=34 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref> The proceedings were handled by the N\u00f6rdlingen city council, which in common with other [[Free Imperial Cities]] at the time, functioned as both executive and judiciary.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Isenmann |first1=Eberhard |title=Gesetzgebung und Gesetzgebungsrecht sp\u00e4tmittelalterlicher deutscher St\u00e4dte |journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr historische Forschung |date=2001 |volume=28 |pages=1-94, 161-261}}</ref> \n\nProceedings were made more complex by the fact that three of the women who had witnessed events surrounding the alleged abortion had left N\u00f6rdlingen by the time the investigation began. Els herself had gone to [[Wei\u00dfenburg in Bayern]], while Margrette von Biberach and Ursel von Konstanz had both gone to [[Nuremberg]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=6 |issue=69 |page=34 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref>\n\n===Inquiry into working conditions===\n\nProceedings in N\u00f6rdlingen began with the inquiry into the working conditions in the brothel. Each woman working there at the time of the investigation was first asked a set of questions pertaining to how they had been treated by Lienhart and Barbara, and whether they had experienced specific abuses at their hands. The first witness was named Anna von Ulm, whose testimony supplied the majority of the evidence. Those who followed her were named Adelhait von Sindelfingen, Anna von Schaffhausen, Catrin von N\u00fcrnberg, Ch\u00fcndlin von Augsburg, Cristina von der Etsch, Els von N\u00fcrnberg, Enndlin von Schaffhausen, Margrette von Biberach, and W\u00ffchselbrunn von Ulm. Another woman, Ursel von Konstanz, had since left N\u00f6rdlingen to work in Nuremberg's public brothel; she was therefore interrogated by the Nuremberg city council at the request of the council in N\u00f6rdlingen, who received a copy of her statement. \n\nThe women's testimony revealed a widespread pattern of abuse and exploitation at the hands of Lienhart Fryermut and Barbara Tarschenfeindin. This included practices such as forcing the women to work while menstruating; forcing them to work on holy days; denying them the chance to go to church to hear Mass; confiscating their clothes and forcing them to buy items from them at excessive prices; feeding them disgusting food; forcing them to spin cloth to generate extra income; seizing tips given to them by customers and taking more than the permitted one-third cut from their wages. Many of the women said they had routinely suffered violence at Lienhart's hands, and that he sometimes used a bullwhip to beat them. Almost all of the women stated that they were in debt to Lienhart and as a consequence were unable to leave the brothel, notwithstanding the fact that he forbade them to leave the building most of the time.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=6 |issue=69 |pages=34-36 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref> \n\n===The abortion inquiry===\n\nAs well as testifying about working conditions in the brothel, many of the women also described the events surrounding the alleged abortion of Els von Eystett's child, including Els herself. Els claimed in her own statement that she had first complained of abdominal pains to Barbara. Barbara had told her that she was merely suffering from [[amenorrhea]], and stated that she would mix up a drink to bring on menstruation. Having dispatched Anna von Ulm and Margrette von Biberach to fetch ingredients from the market, Barbara then mixed together [[Vinca|periwinkle]], cloves, carrot (likely to have been [[daucus carota]], a known abortifacient) and strong wine into a hot draught, which, Els claimed, she was forced to drink.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=6 |issue=69 |page=30 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref>  \n\nSeveral witnesses including Els, Margrette von Biberach and Anna von Ulm testified that the drink rapidly brought on strong abdominal pains. This caused Els to miscarried a male foetus which Els herself estimated to be twenty weeks old. After her miscarriage Els was forced to return to work, and revealed to at least one customer what had happened to her. After rumours of what had happened had reached the city council, but before the latter had acted, Barbara and Lienhart agreed to release Els from her debts and allow her to leave the brothel, on the condition that she not reveal what had happened; having left N\u00f6rdlingen, Els subsequently went to [[Wei\u00dfenburg in Bayern]], where she was eventually tracked down after the investigation was launched in N\u00f6rdlingen.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=6 |issue=69 |page=30 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref>\n\n===Consequences of the investigation===\n\nFollowing the interrogation of the women of N\u00f6rdlingen's brothel, both Lienhart Fryermut and Barbara Tarschenfeindin were themselves interrogated. Barbara was found guilty of causing the abortion of Els von Eystett's child. Although N\u00f6rdlingen's town law contained no explicit reference to abortion,<ref>{{cite book |last1=M\u00fcller |first1=Karl Otto |title=N\u00f6rdlinger Stadtrechte des Mittelalters |date=1933 |publisher=Verlag der Kommission f\u00fcr Bayerische Landesgeschichte |location=Munich}}</ref> convictions of abortion in German-speaking towns in the fifteenth century usually resulted in the expulsion of the guilty party.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=ex and Secrecy: A Secular Prosecution of Abortion in Fourteenth-Century Zurich |journal=The Medi\u00e6val Journal |date=2015 |volume=5 |issue=1 |page=86}}</ref> Barbara was consequently put on the pillory before being branded across the forehead and banished across the Rhine in perpetuity.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=6 |issue=69 |page=37 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref> \n\nLienhart was dismissed from his post as brothel-keeper and forced to swear an oath (the ''Urfehde'') in which he renounced the right to take vengeance and acknowledged his own banishment from the town.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Schuster |first1=Peter |editor1-last=Blauert |editor1-first=Andreas |editor2-last=Schwerhoff |editor2-first=Gerd |title=Mit den Waffen der Justiz. Zur Kriminalit\u00e4tsgeschichte des sp\u00e4ten Mittelalters und der Fr\u00fchen Neuzeit |date=1993 |location=Frankfurt am Main |page=17 |chapter=Hinaus oder ins Frauenhaus. Weibliche Sexualit\u00e4t und gesellschaftliche Kontrolle an der Wende vom Mittelalter zur Neuzeit}}</ref>\n\nIn 1472, a new ordinance (''Frauenhausordnung'') was drawn up for the running of N\u00f6rdlingen's brothel containing a number of provisions intended to prevent abuses of the kind reported by the women at the investigation. The extent to which these new rules were ever in force is nevertheless doubtful as the ordinance was never bound into the town's collection of statutes.</ref> Barbara was consequently put on the pillory before being branded across the forehead and banished across the Rhine in perpetuity.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=6 |issue=69 |page=37 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref> \n\nNo further historical records pertaining to Els von Eystett survive; after giving her testimony, nothing more is known of her life.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{Prostitution in Germany}}\n\n[[Category:German prostitutes]]\n[[Category:Women of medieval Germany]]\n[[Category:15th-century German people]]\n[[Category:15th-century crime]]\n[[Category:Medieval criminals]]\n", "text_old": "'''Els von Eystett''' (also Els von Eichst\u00e4tt) was woman who worked in a public [[brothel]] in [[N\u00f6rdlingen]], Germany, in the late fifteenth century. Els originally worked in the brothel as a kitchen maid and later as a prostitute. Her experiences are documented in the records of a criminal investigation carried out by the city council of N\u00f6rdlingen between December 1471 and January 1472. \n\nThe investigation was first prompted by rumours that Els had become pregnant by a customer, and had subsequently been forced by the brothel madam to terminate her pregnancy by means of a herbal [[abortifacient]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Schuster |first1=Peter |title=Das Frauenhaus. St\u00e4dtische Bordelle in Deutschland 1350-1600 |date=1992 |publisher=F. Sch\u00f6ningh |page=92|isbn=9783506782519}}</ref> The inquiry later expanded to involve the interrogation of all twelve women working in N\u00f6rdlingen's brothel in the latter half of 1471, as well as the brothel madam Barbara Tarscheinfeindin and brothel-keeper Lienhart Fryermut. As several of the women in the brothel had left N\u00f6rdlingen by the time the interrogations began (including Els herself) the investigation also involved cooperation between the authorities in N\u00f6rdlingen and the city councils of [[Nuremberg]] and [[Wei\u00dfenburg in Bayern]]. \n\nOriginal transcriptions of the women's testimony are held today in [https://www.noerdlingen.de/verwaltung/einrichtungen/archiv/ N\u00f6rdlingen's civic archive]. The case record offers the most comprehensive vision of prostitution currently known to have survived from medieval Europe which shows the perspectives of prostitutes themselves.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=69 |issue=6 |pages=28-39 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref> Els's story has been the subject of several magazine articles,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=69 |issue=6 |pages=28-39 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref> <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Thadeusz |first1=Frank |title=Paar des Grauens |journal=Der Spiegel |date=15 June 2019|volume=2019 |issue=25 |url=https://magazin.spiegel.de/SP/2019/25/164407550/}}</ref> a TV documentary,<ref>{{cite web |title=K\u00e4ufliche Liebe im Mittelalter. Wie Wanderhuren wirklich lebten |url=https://bilderfest.de/index.php?article_id=51&clang=0 |website=Bilderfest GmbH}}</ref> and a theatrical production,<ref>{{cite web |title=Els - Die Frauenhausakte von N\u00f6rdlingen |url=http://www.freilichtbuehne-noerdlingen.de/index.php |website=Freilichtb\u00fchne N\u00f6rdlingen}}</ref> and has been the focus of modern research into prostitution in medieval Europe. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Schuster |first1=Peter |editor1-last=H\u00f6dl |editor1-first=G\u00fcnther |editor2-last=Mayrhofer |editor2-first=Fritz |editor3-last=Opll |editor3-first=Ferdinand |title=Stadt der Frauen |date=2003 |location=Linz |pages=265-91 |language=German |chapter=Lebensbedingungen der Prostituierten in der sp\u00e4tmittelalterlichen Stadt}}</ref> <ref>{{cite book |last1=Schuster |first1=Peter |title=Das Frauenhaus. St\u00e4dtische Bordelle in Deutschland 1350-1600 |publisher=F. Sch\u00f6ningh |location=Paderborn |pages=11, 92, 113}}</ref> <ref>{{cite journal |last1=R\u00e4uschel |first1=Lara-Sophie |title=Das N\u00f6rdlinger Frauenhaus und die Justiz. Der Abtreibungsfall der Dirne Els von Eystett (Reichsstadt N\u00f6rdlingen, Reichsstadt Wei\u00dfenburg) |journal=Historischer Verein f\u00fcr N\u00f6rdlingen und das Ries Jahrbuch |date=2014 |issue=35 |pages=1-35}}</ref>\n\n===Prostitution in medieval Europe===\n\nPublic brothels of the kind that Els von Eystett worked in were a common feature in towns across much of western Europe in the period ca. 1350-1550.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mazo Karras |first1=Ruth |editor1-last=Brundage |editor1-first=James A. |editor2-last=Bullough |editor2-first=Vern L. |title=Handbook of Medieval Sexuality |date=2000 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |location=New York |pages=244-5 |chapter=Prostitution in Medieval Europe}}</ref> Although the medieval Church condemned prostitution and saw prostitutes themselves as sinful women,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Brundage |first1=James A. |title=Prostitution in the Medieval Canon Law |journal=Signs |date=1976 |volume=1 |issue=4 |page=830}}</ref> it was generally accepted that tolerating prostituion in society represented a lesser evil than banning it altogether.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mazo Karras |first1=Ruth |editor1-last=Brundage |editor1-first=James A. |editor2-last=Bullough |editor2-first=Vern L. |title=Handbook of Medieval Sexuality |publisher=Taylor & Francis |location=New York |page=245 |chapter=Prostitution in Medieval Europe}}</ref> This position was upheld by a number of major ecclesiastical figures including [[St. Augustine]] <ref>{{cite book |last1=Augustine |editor1-last=Green |editor1-first=W. M. |title=Sancti Aurelii Augustini: Contra academicos; De beata vita; De ordine (Corpus Christianorum Series Latina 29) |date=1970 |location=Turnhout |page=114}}</ref> and [[St. Thomas Aquinas]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dever |first1=Vincent |title=Aquinas and the Practice of Prostitution |journal=Essays in Medieval Studies |date=1996 |volume=13 |pages=39-49}}</ref>\n\nIn southern and central Germany, where public brothels were much more common than in the north,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hemmie |first1=Dagmar M. H. |title=Ungeordnete Unzucht. Prostitution im Hanseraum (12.-16. Jahrhundert). L\u00fcbeck - Bergen - Helsing\u00f8r |date=2007 |publisher=B\u00f6hlau |location=Cologne |page=126}}</ref> brothels typically operated on a leaseholder model which saw a brothel-keeper (''Frauenwirt/in'') pay civic authorities for the right to run the brothel. Rules governing the relationship between brothel-keepers and the authorites were set out in lease agreements, and frequently in oaths sworn by brothel-keepers which required them to make promises of loyalty and obedience. These documents frequently also contained 'house rules' specifying the behaviour forbidden in brothels (such as drunkenness and blasphemy) and governing the relations between prostitutes and the brothel-keeper.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Isenmann |first1=Eberhard |title=Die Deutsche Stadt im Mittelalter, 1150-1550 |date=2012 |publisher=B\u00f6hlau |location=Vienna |page=475}}</ref> \n\nProstitutes themselves typically lived in the brothel, and as well as paying for board and lodging were required to give the brothel-keeper a certain amount of the money they received from clients. This usually amounted to one third of their earnings.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Peter |first1=Schuster |title=Das Frauenhaus. St\u00e4dtische Bordelle in Deutschland 1350-1600 |date=1992 |publisher=F. Sch\u00f6ningh |location=Paderborn |page=113}}</ref> Most cities permitted brothel-keepers to contract debts with prostitutes or to accept women as pawns, requiring them to pay off debts through their labour. Partly as a consequence of this, prostitutes were often heavily in debt to brothel-keepers, and many were traded between brothels.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schuster |first1=Beate |title=Frauenhandel und Frauenh\u00e4user im 15. und im 16. Jahrhundert |journal=VSWG: Vierteljahrschrift f\u00fcr Sozial- und Wirtschaftsgeschichte |date=1991 |volume=2 |issue=78}}</ref> \n\n===The N\u00f6rdlingen investigations of 1471-2===\n\nThe transcriptions produced from the testimony of Els von Eystett and the other women of N\u00f6rdlingen's brothel form the primary source of information about the investigation. Sentencing records for Barbara Tarschenfeindin and Lienhart Fryermut are also held in N\u00f6rdlingen's civic archive in the city's so-called blood book (''Blutbuch''), a medieval and early modern record of criminal punishments, and the town's collection of ''[https://www.historisches-lexikon-bayerns.de/Lexikon/Urfehden Urfehden]'', a form of judicial oath.\n\nThe women's statements indicate that the investigation proceeded along two lines: a specific inquiry into the rumours of Els's abortion, and a more general inquiry into the working conditions in the brothel, ostensibly prompted by Els's claims of other abuses by Barbara and Lienhart.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=6 |issue=69 |page=34 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref> The proceedings were handled by the N\u00f6rdlingen city council, which in common with other [[Free Imperial Cities]] at the time, functioned as both executive and judiciary.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Isenmann |first1=Eberhard |title=Gesetzgebung und Gesetzgebungsrecht sp\u00e4tmittelalterlicher deutscher St\u00e4dte |journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr historische Forschung |date=2001 |volume=28 |pages=1-94, 161-261}}</ref> \n\nProceedings were made more complex by the fact that three of the women who had witnessed events surrounding the alleged abortion had left N\u00f6rdlingen by the time the investigation began. Els herself had gone to [[Wei\u00dfenburg in Bayern]], while Margrette von Biberach and Ursel von Konstanz had both gone to [[Nuremberg]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=6 |issue=69 |page=34 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref>\n\n===Inquiry into working conditions===\n\nProceedings in N\u00f6rdlingen began with the inquiry into the working conditions in the brothel. Each woman working there at the time of the investigation was first asked a set of questions pertaining to how they had been treated by Lienhart and Barbara, and whether they had experienced specific abuses at their hands. The first witness was named Anna von Ulm, whose testimony supplied the majority of the evidence. Those who followed her were named Adelhait von Sindelfingen, Anna von Schaffhausen, Catrin von N\u00fcrnberg, Ch\u00fcndlin von Augsburg, Cristina von der Etsch, Els von N\u00fcrnberg, Enndlin von Schaffhausen, Margrette von Biberach, and W\u00ffchselbrunn von Ulm. Another woman, Ursel von Konstanz, had since left N\u00f6rdlingen to work in Nuremberg's public brothel; she was therefore interrogated by the Nuremberg city council at the request of the council in N\u00f6rdlingen, who received a copy of her statement. \n\nThe women's testimony revealed a widespread pattern of abuse and exploitation at the hands of Lienhart Fryermut and Barbara Tarschenfeindin. This included practices such as forcing the women to work while menstruating; forcing them to work on holy days; denying them the chance to go to church to hear Mass; confiscating their clothes and forcing them to buy items from them at excessive prices; feeding them disgusting food; forcing them to spin cloth to generate extra income; seizing tips given to them by customers and taking more than the permitted one-third cut from their wages. Many of the women said they had routinely suffered violence at Lienhart's hands, and that he sometimes used a bullwhip to beat them. Almost all of the women stated that they were in debt to Lienhart and as a consequence were unable to leave the brothel, notwithstanding the fact that he forbade them to leave the building most of the time.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=6 |issue=69 |pages=34-36 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref> \n\n===The abortion inquiry===\n\nAs well as testifying about working conditions in the brothel, many of the women also described the events surrounding the alleged abortion of Els von Eystett's child, including Els herself. Els claimed in her own statement that she had first complained of abdominal pains to Barbara. Barbara had told her that she was merely suffering from [[amenorrhea]], and stated that she would mix up a drink to bring on menstruation. Having dispatched Anna von Ulm and Margrette von Biberach to fetch ingredients from the market, Barbara then mixed together [[Vinca|periwinkle]], cloves, carrot (likely to have been [[daucus carota]], a known abortifacient) and strong wine into a hot draught, which, Els claimed, she was forced to drink.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=6 |issue=69 |page=30 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref>  \n\nSeveral witnesses including Els, Margrette von Biberach and Anna von Ulm testified that the drink rapidly brought on strong abdominal pains. This caused Els to miscarried a male foetus which Els herself estimated to be twenty weeks old. After her miscarriage Els was forced to return to work, and revealed to at least one customer what had happened to her. After rumours of what had happened had reached the city council, but before the latter had acted, Barbara and Lienhart agreed to release Els from her debts and allow her to leave the brothel, on the condition that she not reveal what had happened; having left N\u00f6rdlingen, Els subsequently went to [[Wei\u00dfenburg in Bayern]], where she was eventually tracked down after the investigation was launched in N\u00f6rdlingen.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=6 |issue=69 |page=30 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref>\n\n===Consequences of the investigation===\n\nFollowing the interrogation of the women of N\u00f6rdlingen's brothel, both Lienhart Fryermut and Barbara Tarschenfeindin were themselves interrogated. Barbara was found guilty of causing the abortion of Els von Eystett's child. Although N\u00f6rdlingen's town law contained no explicit reference to abortion,<ref>{{cite book |last1=M\u00fcller |first1=Karl Otto |title=N\u00f6rdlinger Stadtrechte des Mittelalters |date=1933 |publisher=Verlag der Kommission f\u00fcr Bayerische Landesgeschichte |location=Munich}}</ref> convictions of abortion in German-speaking towns in the fifteenth century usually resulted in the expulsion of the guilty party.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=ex and Secrecy: A Secular Prosecution of Abortion in Fourteenth-Century Zurich |journal=The Medi\u00e6val Journal |date=2015 |volume=5 |issue=1 |page=86}}</ref> Barbara was consequently put on the pillory before being branded across the forehead and banished across the Rhine in perpetuity.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=6 |issue=69 |page=37 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref> \n\nLienhart was dismissed from his post as brothel-keeper and forced to swear an oath (the ''Urfehde'') in which he renounced the right to take vengeance and acknowledged his own banishment from the town.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Schuster |first1=Peter |editor1-last=Blauert |editor1-first=Andreas |editor2-last=Schwerhoff |editor2-first=Gerd |title=Mit den Waffen der Justiz. Zur Kriminalit\u00e4tsgeschichte des sp\u00e4ten Mittelalters und der Fr\u00fchen Neuzeit |date=1993 |location=Frankfurt am Main |page=17 |chapter=Hinaus oder ins Frauenhaus. Weibliche Sexualit\u00e4t und gesellschaftliche Kontrolle an der Wende vom Mittelalter zur Neuzeit}}</ref>\n\nIn 1472, a new ordinance (''Frauenhausordnung'') was drawn up for the running of N\u00f6rdlingen's brothel containing a number of provisions intended to prevent abuses of the kind reported by the women at the investigation. The extent to which these new rules were ever in force is nevertheless doubtful as the ordinance was never bound into the town's collection of statutes.</ref> Barbara was consequently put on the pillory before being branded across the forehead and banished across the Rhine in perpetuity.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Page |first1=Jamie |title=Inside the Medieval Brothel |journal=History Today |date=June 2019 |volume=6 |issue=69 |page=37 |url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/feature/inside-medieval-brothel}}</ref> \n\nNo further historical records pertaining to Els von Eystett survive; after giving her testimony, nothing more is known of her life.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{Prostitution in Germany}}\n\n[[Category:German prostitutes]]\n[[Category:Women of medieval Germany]]\n[[Category:15th-century German people]]\n[[Category:15th-century crime]]\n[[Category:Medieval criminals]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProstitution in medieval Europe:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: authorites \u2192 authorities, prostituion \u2192 prostitution, 1350-1550 \u2192 1350\u20131550", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Els_von_Eystett"}
{"title_page": "Prostitution in Nepal", "text_new": "'''Prostitution in Nepal''' is  illegal. The Human Trafficking and Transportation (Control) Act, 2064, Act Number 5 of the Year 2064 (2008), criminalises [[prostitution]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Part 4 \u2013 Human Trafficking and Transportation (Control) Act, 2064 |url=http://www.lawcommission.gov.np/en/archives/12259 |website=Nepal Law Commission |accessdate=17 April 2019 |quote=Section 15(d)}}</ref> and living of the earnings of prostitution by including it in the definition of [[human trafficking]].<ref name=\"spl\">{{cite web|title=Sex Work Law - Countries|url=http://spl.ids.ac.uk/sexworklaw/countries|website=Sexuality, Poverty and Law|accessdate=31 March 2018|language=en}}</ref> [[UNAIDS]] estimate there to be 67,300 prostitutes in the country.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sex workers: Population size estimate - Number, 2016 |url=http://www.aidsinfoonline.org/gam/stock/shared/dv/PivotData_2018_7_22_636678151733621264.htm |website=www.aidsinfoonline.org |publisher=UNAIDS |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Government policies==\nAlthough there are no laws in Nepal criminalizing sex work specifically, there are some laws that were enacted throughout the 1980s that criminalize trafficking within and outside of Nepal that are used towards sex work.<ref name=\"Shukla\">{{cite web|last=Shukla|first=Rakesh|title=Sex Work and Laws in South Asia: A Monograph|date=April 2010|series=Monograph Ser. 4|pages=21\u201326|url=http://sangram.org/Download/Laws_in_south_asia.pdf|accessdate=25 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826164334/http://sangram.org/Download/Laws_in_south_asia.pdf |archive-date=26 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Hennink\">{{cite journal|last=Hennink|first=Monique|author2=Padam Simkhada |title=Sex Trafficking in Nepal: Context and Process|journal=Opportunities and Choices Writing Paper|year=2004|url=http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/34733/1/Sex%20trafficking%20WP11.PDF|accessdate=15 April 2012}}</ref> Many of these laws are sometimes interpreted to accuse sex workers as well, which comes from a lack of knowledge in the distinction between the sex trafficking scene and sex work. Sex work is a term used to refer to all aspects of the lawful and unlawful sex industries around the world.<ref name=\"kimberly\">{{cite book|last1=Hoang|first1=Kimberly Kay|title=Dealing in Desire - Asian Ascendancy, Western Decline, and the Hidden Currencies of Global Sex Work|date=February 2015|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520275577|url=https://www.ucpress.edu/book.php?isbn=9780520275577|language=en}}</ref> There are various forms of sex work, including physical and verbal forms. This distinction is one that is not truly understood; thus, many of the policies and laws enacted within Nepal against trafficking\u2014many argue\u2014should not be applied to sex work. Authorities and laws trying to stop true slavery\u2014trafficking\u2014get misapplied to sex workers, clients and others involved in the sex industry.\n\nIn 1986, the Traffic in Humans (Control) Act was passed in Nepal and was aimed at stopping trafficking in the form of prostitution.<ref name=\"Hennink\" /> However, this act, like many others, proved to be ineffective, mainly due to the fact that the act was \u201clargely aimed at criminalizing prostitution rather than curbing trafficking activities.\u201d<ref name=\"Hennink\" />\n\nIn 2008, the Human Trafficking and Transportation (Control) Act, criminalised prostitution and living of the earnings of prostitution by including it in the definition of human trafficking.<ref name=\"spl\" />\n\n==Reasons for entering the sex industry==\nFor many, entering into the sex industry is the only way in which they could survive economically in Nepal.<ref name=\"Hennink\" /> However, sex work is not officially recognized among the industrial or service sectors of labor. There is a large case of [[sex trafficking]] in Nepal, but voluntary sex work is more common than many believe.\n\nAmong the developing poor nations throughout Southeast Asia today, Nepal remains one of the most poverty-stricken. Research shows that about 38% of the Nepali population is living under US$1 per day, and 82% under US$2 per day.<ref name=\"Hennink\" /> Due to this high rate of poverty, the rural poor Nepalese people generally have large families, are landless or have very small landholdings, have high rates of illiteracy and are concentrated in specific ethnic, caste and minority groups.<ref name=\"RuralPoverty\">{{cite web|title=Rural Poverty in Nepal|url=http://www.ruralpovertyportal.org/web/guest/country/home/tags/nepal|website=Rural Poverty Portal|accessdate=18 March 2012}}</ref> These issues of poverty are part of why many people, including both cisgender and transgender men and women, go into the sex industry in Nepal. Due to their large families, these sex workers need to find a way to help out within the household. More specifically, there are not many opportunities for the women sex workers, and women in general, to break out of the domestic environment and duties which have left them in poverty, so the only option left for them is going into sex work.<ref name=\"Hennink\" />\n\nNepal, like many other Southeast Asian countries, has a limited amount of resources for women. Recently, the Nepalese government has recognized more rights for women in terms of family involvement, physical integrity, ownership rights, and overall civil liberties.<ref name=\"GenderEquality\">{{cite web|title=Gender Equality and Social Institutions in Nepal|url=http://genderindex.org/country/nepal|website=Social Institutions & Gender Index|accessdate=5 April 2012}}</ref> However, this does not change the fact that women are still highly underrepresented in Nepalese society, and do not have the same rights that men do.<ref name=\"Hennink\" />\n\nWomen constitute a majority of these sex workers, because they rarely have any opportunities otherwise. These women may feel empowered by the work that they do, in the sense that they can better provide for their families, and be seen for something other than what society treats women. In some cases, girls that are put into the sex industry are forced to migrate to carpet factories outside of Nepal or in more centralized cities by their families to better provide for them. After a while, they are either abducted into the traffic scene, or coerced to join.<ref name=\"Hennink\" /> The issue of poverty has driven many families in Nepal to desperation, to the point of putting their daughters out on the streets to earn money to help out in the home.<ref name=\"Richardson\">{{cite web|last=Richardson|first=Erin|title=Nepal Sex Trade|url=http://www1.american.edu/TED/nepalsex.htm|website=TED Case Studies|accessdate=14 April 2012|date=17 November 1998}}</ref>\n\n[[Human trafficking in Nepal]]\u2014more specifically, sex trafficking\u2014is a common precursor to voluntary sex work. After escaping from the sex trafficking world, women return to sex work when they return to Nepal,<ref name=\"Hennink\" /> for it is the only thing they know.\n\n==Consequences of sex work==\nSex work in Nepal can be a short-term relief to the poverty and struggles encountered by these hundreds of women on a daily basis. The long-term effects bring a new perspective to sex work, and are a big part of the argument against sex work.\n\n===Short-term consequences===\nMany people go into the sex work field in hopes of finding a better opportunity for their families and for themselves. This is especially true in Nepal, which is ranked as one of the countries with the lowest human development indicators in the world, ranked 143 in the [[United Nations Human Development Index]],<ref name=\"Hennink\" /> with an HDI of 0.458.<ref name=\"NepalProfile\">{{cite web|title=Nepal Country Profile: Human Development Indicators|url=http://hdrstats.undp.org/en/countries/profiles/NPL.html|website=International Human Development Indicators|accessdate=14 April 2012|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415135354/http://hdrstats.undp.org/en/countries/profiles/NPL.html|archivedate=15 April 2012|df=}}</ref>  Because sex workers usually belong to the lower castes of the caste system within Nepal (a survey conducted by UN Nepal, showed that the majority of the sex workers were from Tamangs and Dalits), India, and other Southeast Asian countries, they feel as though sex work is the only opportunity that they truly have to better their lives and that of their families. The [[Nepalese caste system]] makes it very difficult for people of any class to rise up to a higher class. There have been rare instances in which members of a specific class have risen, and even in these cases, the members only rise within their own caste (see also [[Nepalese caste system]]). Due to this social trap, sex work is seen as a way to escape from the social organization. Sex work can allow those in lower castes to provide for their family in a different way.<ref name=\"Richardson\" /> In the short-term, going into the sex industry would seem like a logical solution, since the money that many of these sex workers make can go towards the improvement of their families.\n\n===Long-term consequences===\nSex workers are exposed to a variety of serious risks, including: sexually transmitted diseases, a decrease in security, and a loss of human rights.\n\n====Sexually transmitted diseases====\n{{see also|HIV/AIDS in Nepal}}\nNepal faces increasing HIV prevalence among most at-risk populations (MARPs) such as sex workers, injecting drug users (IDUs), men who have sex with men (MSM), and migrants.<ref name=\"Upadhya\">{{cite journal|last=Upadhya|first=Raji|author2=Erik Nora |title=HIV/AIDS in Nepal|journal=The World Bank|date=August 2008|url=http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTSAREGTOPHIVAIDS/Resources/496350-1217345766462/HIV-AIDS-brief-Aug08-NP.pdf|accessdate=18 March 2012}}</ref> Since 1988, when the first case of [[HIV/AIDS in Nepal]] was reported, more than 1,750 cases of AIDS and over 11,000 cases of HIV infection were officially reported. Since Nepal is limited in terms of its public health surveillance system, the actual number of infections throughout the country is said to be more. [[UNAIDS]] estimates that approximately 30,000 people were living with HIV in 2018. HIV prevalence amongst sex workers was estimated to be 4.2%, compated to 0.1% for the general population<ref name=\"UNAIDS\">{{cite web|title=Nepal|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/regionscountries/countries/nepal/|website=UNAIDS: Joined United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS|accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Compromised security====\nThe entry of women into sex work can sometimes take an unexpected turn. Although some women go into the sex industry voluntarily, they can end up being taken into the larger sex trafficking scene to India and surrounding areas. The trafficking of women and girls to India is a major problem which has made international news. Every year, a rough estimate of about 7,000 Nepali girls are trafficked to India, where they are forced into prostitution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soschildrensvillages.org.uk/charity-news/archive/2009/02/nepali-girls-traffick-india- |title=More than 200,000 Nepali girls trafficked to Indian red light areas \u2014 SOS Children |publisher=Soschildrensvillages.org.uk |date=2009-02-19 |accessdate=2011-10-15}}</ref> Nepalese women and girls, especially virgins, are favored in India, because of their fair skin and young looks (see also [[Human trafficking in Nepal]]).\n\nSince the policy of an open border between China and Nepal, a large number of Nepalese women in recent years have been sold into prostitution or as brides to Chinese men.<ref name=\"slavetrade\">[http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Kathmandu-opens-borders-with-China-and-triggers-slave-trade-27819.html Kathmandu opens borders with China and triggers slave trade]</ref>\n\nAside from being kidnapped into the trafficking scene, sex workers run the risk of being abused sexually against their will. When things like this happen, it is hard for these sex workers to get protection, because they are seen as criminals.<ref name=\"SexandMoney\">{{cite web|title=Sex and Money: A National Search for Human Worth|website=Film|accessdate=14 April 2012|year=2011|url=http://sexandmoneyfilm.com/}}</ref> This is one of the reasons that many are fighting to legalize voluntary sex work. Many argue that these people deserve protection against harm, just like those that are taken into the trafficking scene.\n\n====Loss of human rights====\nWhen living a life in the sex industry, many argue that the risk of losing human rights is common. Many times, especially in Nepal, the sex industry is run by organized crime.<ref name=\"Pyle\">{{cite journal|last=Pyle|first=Jean L.|title=Sex, Maids, and Export Processing: Risks and Reasons for Gendered Global Productions Networks|journal=International Journal of Politics, Culture, and Society|year=2001|volume=15|issue=1|pages=55\u201376|jstor=20000175|doi=10.1023/A:1011167800391}}</ref> The sex industry contributes between 2\u201314% of [[gross domestic product]] in countries such as Nepal.<ref name=\"Pyle\" /> Due to this, there is a great incentive for corruption as far as within officials and the police.<ref name=\"Pyle\" /> \u201cThis puts women sex workers in vulnerable positions because the institution mandated to protect people either ignores their problems or takes part in the abuse.\u201d<ref name=\"Pyle\" /> If sex workers were to challenge the authority of these officials\u2014even by demanding control over their own bodies\u2014they are running the risk of being punished within the community and even the law. This is another controversial issue, in that the suppliers are always the ones being punished, while the demand sector of this industry seems to get away with their equally incriminating actions.<ref name=\"SexandMoney\" /><ref name=\"Pyle\" />\n\n==Sex trafficking==\n{{see also|Human trafficking in Nepal}}\nNepal is a source, transit, and destination country for women and children subjected to [[sex trafficking]]. Nepali women and girls are subjected to sex trafficking in Nepal, [[India]], the [[Middle East]], [[Asia]], and [[Sub-Saharan Africa]]. Unregistered migrants, including the large number of Nepalis who travel through India or rely on unregistered recruiting agents, are particularly vulnerable to sex trafficking. Some migrants from [[Bangladesh]], [[Sri Lanka]], and possibly other countries transit Nepal en route to employment in the Middle East, using potentially falsified Nepali travel documents, and may be subjected to human trafficking. Some government officials reportedly accept bribes to include false information in Nepali identity documents or provide fraudulent documents to prospective labor migrants, a tactic used by unscrupulous recruiters to evade recruitment regulations.  Many Nepalis, including children, whose home or livelihood was destroyed by the [[April 2015 Nepal earthquake|2015 earthquakes]] continue to be vulnerable to trafficking. Traffickers increasingly utilize social media and mobile technologies to lure and deceive their victims.<ref name=\"state18\">{{cite web |title=Nepal 2018 Trafficking in Persons Report |url=https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2018/282717.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729230801/https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2018/282717.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 July 2018 |website=U.S. Department of State |accessdate=29 July 2018}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Department of State]] [[Office to Monitor and Combat Trafficking in Persons]] ranks Nepal as a '[[Trafficking in Persons Report#Ranking System|Tier 2]]' country.<ref name=\"state18\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[HIV/AIDS in Nepal]]\n* [[Sex Trafficking]]\n* [[Sex workers]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Gomare et al. (2002) ''Adopting strategic approach for reaching out to inaccessible population viz'' Abstract WePeF6707F abstract, The XIV International AIDS Conference.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.hrw.org/reports/1995/India.htm Rape For Profit -- Human Rights Watch Report]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120624061509/http://www.uri.edu/artsci/wms/hughes/india.htm India - Facts on Trafficking and Prostitution from the Coalition Against Trafficking in Women (CATW)]\n* [http://womennewsnetwork.net/2008/12/05/lostdaughternepal808/ Lost Daughters - An Ongoing Tragedy in Nepal], Women News Network - WNN, Dec 05, 2008\n\n{{Asia in topic|Prostitution in}}\n\n[[Category:Prostitution in Nepal| ]]\n[[Category:Nepalese society]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nepal]]\n", "text_old": "'''Prostitution in Nepal''' is  illegal. The Human Trafficking and Transportation (Control) Act, 2064, Act Number 5 of the Year 2064 (2008), criminalises [[prostitution]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Part 4 \u2013 Human Trafficking and Transportation (Control) Act, 2064 |url=http://www.lawcommission.gov.np/en/archives/12259 |website=Nepal Law Commission |accessdate=17 April 2019 |quote=Section 15(d)}}</ref> and living of the earnings of prostitution by including it in the definition of [[human trafficking]].<ref name=\"spl\">{{cite web|title=Sex Work Law - Countries|url=http://spl.ids.ac.uk/sexworklaw/countries|website=Sexuality, Poverty and Law|accessdate=31 March 2018|language=en}}</ref> [[UNAIDS]] estimate there to be 67,300 prostitutes in the country.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sex workers: Population size estimate - Number, 2016 |url=http://www.aidsinfoonline.org/gam/stock/shared/dv/PivotData_2018_7_22_636678151733621264.htm |website=www.aidsinfoonline.org |publisher=UNAIDS |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Government policies==\nAlthough there are no laws in Nepal criminalizing sex work specifically, there are some laws that were enacted throughout the 1980s that criminalize trafficking within and outside of Nepal that are used towards sex work.<ref name=\"Shukla\">{{cite web|last=Shukla|first=Rakesh|title=Sex Work and Laws in South Asia: A Monograph|date=April 2010|series=Monograph Ser. 4|pages=21\u201326|url=http://sangram.org/Download/Laws_in_south_asia.pdf|accessdate=25 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826164334/http://sangram.org/Download/Laws_in_south_asia.pdf |archive-date=26 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Hennink\">{{cite journal|last=Hennink|first=Monique|author2=Padam Simkhada |title=Sex Trafficking in Nepal: Context and Process|journal=Opportunities and Choices Writing Paper|year=2004|url=http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/34733/1/Sex%20trafficking%20WP11.PDF|accessdate=15 April 2012}}</ref> Many of these laws are sometimes interpreted to accuse sex workers as well, which comes from a lack of knowledge in the distinction between the sex trafficking scene and sex work. Sex work is a term used to refer to all aspects of the lawful and unlawful sex industries around the world.<ref name=\"kimberly\">{{cite book|last1=Hoang|first1=Kimberly Kay|title=Dealing in Desire - Asian Ascendancy, Western Decline, and the Hidden Currencies of Global Sex Work|date=February 2015|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520275577|url=https://www.ucpress.edu/book.php?isbn=9780520275577|language=en}}</ref> There are various forms of sex work, including physical and verbal forms. This distinction is one that is not truly understood; thus, many of the policies and laws enacted within Nepal against trafficking\u2014many argue\u2014should not be applied to sex work. Authorities and laws trying to stop true slavery\u2014trafficking\u2014get misapplied to sex workers, clients and others involved in the sex industry.\n\nIn 1986, the Traffic in Humans (Control) Act was passed in Nepal and was aimed at stopping trafficking in the form of prostitution.<ref name=\"Hennink\" /> However, this act, like many others, proved to be ineffective, mainly due